\chapter{Discourse Around Creoles, Cajun, and F\&C}
  \label{chap:discourse}
  The previous two chapters have suggested that Creoles and Cajuns are racialized through examining their linguistic and social structures.
  Linguistically, some subject pronouns are more associated with Creoles and others with Cajuns, allowing the two groups to be marked in their speech as one would expect in a racialized social system, albeit the associations are not categorically complete.
  In terms of social structure, Creoles' personal networks are primarily made up of Creole alters and Cajuns' of Cajun alters.
  The degree of ethnic homophily within their networks is not itself predictive of linguistic structure in a fine-grained way, but this is likely because the homophily is relatively complete, so either one is in the Creole world or one is in the Cajun world with almost no in between.

  Another expectation one would have in a situation where racialization has taken place is that this would be evident in the discourse of Creoles and Cajuns.
  If divisions between the two groups are such that they speak differently and exist is distinct social structures, then this racialization should be salient enough that it comes out in their discourse either explicitly or implicitly.
  Despite it being commonly reported by locals and researchers both that, today, Creoles are Black and Cajuns are White, implying racialization, no in depth discourse analyses have been taken up to examine how this is realized in conversation, although two relatively recent studies have provided relevant data that was examined with a different lenses \parencite{mayeux_racial_2024, wendte_tale_2020}.
  This chapter will thus present a discourse analysis of Creoles and Cajuns with a focus on explicit and implicit expressions of racialization.
  In order to contextualize this discourse, a review will first be presented of discourse themes and phenomena that appear in studies of Blacks and African-Americans in the United States as they constitute a group that has unarguably been racialized.
  The presence of these themes and phenomena in the discourse of Creoles and Cajuns will then be presented.

  \section{Racializing discourse}
    \label{sec:racial_discourse_review}
    What it means for discourse to be racializing may not be immediately clear.
    Racializing discourse has generally been defined as that which ``sorts some people, things, places, and pratices into social categories marked as inherently dangerous and Other'' \parencite[p.~E2]{dick_racializing_2011}.
    Often used as a synonym for racializing discourse is the term \lexi{race talk}, which shares with the above definition that idea that such talk always aims to degrade \parencite{morrison_backs_1993}.
    However, affirming or reaffirming racialized social categories does not necessarily have this goal or impact.
    For example, when Black activists in Oklahoma highlighted the role of race in how their neighborhood was being neglected, they were necessarily engaging in racializing discourse, but it was being put into action to counteract the colorblind racism \parencite{bonilla-silva_racism_2022} of the larger community \parencite[p.~E79]{blanton_chronotopic_2011}.
    Indeed, it has been suggested that marginalized racialized groups should variably choose to discursively transgress against racial logics when they are not beneficial to the group and reaffirm them when needed to draw attention to inequalities born of their racialization \parencite{alim_whos_2016}.
    Naturally, this also means that those who produce or reproduce racial orders through discourse are not necessarily ideologically racist \parencite{hodges_ideologies_2015}.
    When racializing discourse is the expression of ideological racism, latent or not, it is often covert so as to provide plausible deniability in order to avoid possible societal sanctions \parencite[p.~E2]{dick_racializing_2011}.
    The working definition of racializing discourse for the present study is thus any discourse that signals race in some way, overtly or covertly, with positive or with negative intentions or effects.
    In short, it is discourse that produces or reproduces the process of racialization.

    One framework for racializing discourse is the concept of boundaries \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},]{myers_race_2001}.\footnote{
      While boundary concepts such as social closure come from the Weberian tradition rather than the Marxist tradition associated with racialization, this does not render boundaries off-limits here.
      Boundaries between racialized groups plainly exist, as Chapter \ref{chap:networks} demonstrated, and as this chapter will show, those boundaries can be enforced by individual actors.
    }
    Establishing boundaries effectively establishes racialized groups and characterizes them.
    Those boundaries can then be policed or maintained.
    \citeauthor{myers_race_2001} (\citeyear{myers_race_2001}) work is particularly relevant for the current study as they focused on racializing discourses in private conversations which more or less describes the sort of discourse that was collected here.
    They found that boundaries were marked (\foreign{i.e.}, categories were created and characterized) for marginalized groups through racial slurs, caricatures of others, and the dehumanization of anything associated with those groups.
    White people then policed those boundaries by rejecting the right of Black people to exist in White spaces, whereas Black people maintained boundaries instead (\foreign{i.e.}, self-policed).
    The fact that the mechanisms available to the two groups to protect boundaries were indicative of their differing positions in a social hierarchy sets these sort of boundaries apart from those which may be established between groups in non-racializing situations where the marginalization of a people is not inherent to the social structure.

    One group that can undoubtedly be qualified as racialized are Black people in the United States, which has led to English discourse analysis around this group in terms of race and racialization.
    The Creoles of interest for this study being located in the same country as well as the fractal recursivity \parencite{irvine_language_2000} that has equated Creoles with Black people makes the latter a highly relevant comparison group.
    It is thus informative to examine how racialized boundaries are marked for Black people and White people, how White people police these boundaries, and how Black people maintain them.

    % \subsection{Boundary marking}
    Racialized boundaries in the US have been marked out in many ways, naming groups being perhaps the most straightforward way, but another plain way is through the creation of physical boundaries that have persisted since the time of \lexi{de jure} segregation.
    As a result, the theme of neglected, crime-ridden neighborhoods being associated with Black Americans is consistent in discourse not just among White Americans but also among Black Americans who have direct experience with such neighborhoods (\foreign{e.g.}, \citeauthor{becker_linguistic_2014}, \citeyear[p.~46]{becker_linguistic_2014}; \citeauthor{rickford_addressee-_1994}, \citeyear[p.~243]{rickford_addressee-_1994}).
    Additionally, this regular juxtaposition of Black Americans with run-down geographic locations functions as a way of characterizing the people themselves \parencite[p.~E81]{blanton_chronotopic_2011}.
    % Boundaries can coincide with literal physical boundaries that are clear enough for those in the community to comment on and fight over (Blanton 2011)
      % "[B]lack folk" are collocated both in space and discourse with polluted waterways not even fit for horses (Blanton 2011:E81)

    More subtley, pronouns such as \lexi{us} and \lexi{them} can be used to establish that two groups exist that are socially, and in this case racially, differentiated \parencite[p.~E80]{blanton_chronotopic_2011}.
    This is often done by more privileged groups to avoid possibly implicating oneself as racist, whereas marginalized groups 
    For example, as one Lumbee Indian explained, ``[T]hey [American Indians] didn't fool with them [Black Americans], they were scared of them'' \parencite[pp.~178-179]{schilling-estes_constructing_2004}.
    The speaker was himself an American Indian, providing the implicature that these were also his own feelings, but he was able to avoid acknowledging his own racial ideology by speaking through his group instead, allowing for plausible deniability if confronted about the statement.
    A \lexi{they} may also be used by marginalized groups in ways to emphasize their own discrimination and background the importance of who the exact discriminators are \parencite[p.~1020]{perkins_discursive_2019}.
    % For those at the top of the hierarchy, this can be done when beneficial to their discourse whereas the us-them dynamic can be disregarded when not beneficial (Blanton 2011:E83/E86)

    These processes do not stop at defining boundaries and naming those on other side of them but also extend to characterizing what makes each group different.
    In a racialized social system, the marginalized group is thus given negative associations which may be as direct as dehumanizing such people as ``trash'' \parencite[p.~329]{okeke_race_2025}, but typically in the US today, marginalized groups are characterized more covertly as in the above collations between Black Americans and neglected neighborhoods.
    This can manifest in a Black woman being described as ``irritated,'' having ``absolutely no respect,'' and being ``dumber than a box of rocks'' after giving a court testimony \parencite[p.~761]{baugh_swb_2015} to being described as physically imposing to the point of being ``scary'' \parencite[p.~453]{bucholtz_you_1999}, both of which were the sort of characterizations that Black undergraduate students have also reported \parencite[pp.~425-427]{holliday_sociolinguistic_2021}.
    What these characterizations have in common is that they aim to focus on the physicality of Blacks and delegitimize their intelligence, rendering them more like strong animals than thoughtful humans.
    This need not even be with the conscious goal of harming these people as, indeed, the individual who used the ``scary'' descriptor exploited African-American Language to index his own strength, but the impact is the same nonetheless.

    Negative characterizations of marginalized racialized groups are not limited to higher status groups, however, as those who are marginalized may reproduce stereotypes about themselves.
    One example of this is Black Americans judging their own responsibility with money in a negative light \parencite[p.~1018]{perkins_discursive_2019}.
    This particular case involved explicitly contrasting the spending habits of Black Americans with those of a wealthy White man.
    Racializing discourse can become so ingrained in a society that even those who suffer from the resulting social structure may find themselves perpetuating it.
    % And then they may downplay the importance of the discrimination they face as simply how the world is, not even distinguishing their own experience from that of other minority groups (K. Perkins et al. 2019:1020-1021)
      % This is essentially a coping mechanism

    % \subsection{Boundary policing}
    One boundaries have been marked out, they need to be enforced.
    For the privileged group in the racial hierarchy, in this case White Americans, this can consist of making marginalized people unwelcome in public spaces or unwelcome to resources.
    One expression of this is Black people not being able to find institutional redress when falsely accused of wrong-doing \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][p.~3]{labov_facto_1986}.
    Likewise, when attempting to bring to light the wrongs that White Americans have done to them, Black Americans may find themselves facing sanctions rather than the wrong-doers \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][pp.~281-282]{morgan_more_2022}.
    In essence, the sort of public institutions that would deal with these issues are seen as the domains of White Americans.

    Another way to deny Black Americans access to what are treated as White spaces is to place on them the burden of learning new ways of speaking in academic and business contexts where a failure to do so can inhibit one's life chances \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][p.~367]{williams_looking_2010}.
    This burden has been argued to be a reproduction of the Jim Crow logic of separate but equal in that the language of Black 
    Americans is allowed to exist but must not do so in specific spaces \parencite{young_nah_2009}.
    \textcite{holliday_sociolinguistic_2021} called the ``physical, emotional, and psychological effort'' involved in balancing language varieties in this way sociolinguistic labor (p.~421).
    What this might look like in discourse is White Americans looking down on those who do not learn the correct way of speaking and Black Americans engaging in code-switching.

    This \foreign{status quo} of public spaces and resources being treated as the domain of White Americans can ironically be maintained by denying the existence of race when shown to be present in uncomfortable places.
    Denial can be found in euphemisms that allow White Americans to not have to directly deal with race such as \lexi{ethnicity}, \lexi{diversity}, and \lexi{multiculturalism} \parencite[p.~E4]{dick_racializing_2011}.
    Likewise, racialized orders and their role in environmental injustice \parencite{blanton_chronotopic_2011} or the closing of Black schools \parencite[pp.~754-756]{briscoe_that_2015} is disregarded, making it impossible to address these problems.
    Not having to take race into account is a privilege afforded to White Americans and not Black Americans who must always be vigilant even when forming friendships \parencite[p.~11]{wilson_wait_2025} that is further facilitated by folk theories of race that only allow personal, ideological racism to exist and not systemic racism \parencite{hodges_ideologies_2015}.
    Marginalized people are not entirely unaware of this colorblind strategy and so may take terms meant to politely apply to them as euphemisms for the plainly derogatory terms instead \parencite[pp.~E80-E81]{blanton_chronotopic_2011}.
    However, attemping to bring up the racial underpinnings of such discourse can be met with marginalized people being paradoxically accused of being racist themselves (\citeauthor{blanton_chronotopic_2011}, \citeyear[pp.~E83-E84/E88]{blanton_chronotopic_2011}; \citeauthor{briscoe_that_2015}, \citeyear[p.~756]{briscoe_that_2015}).
    Racializing discourse along these lines renders racialized social systems particularly intransigent.
      
    % \subsection{Boundary maintenance}
    White Americans have access not only to the mechanism of boundary policing, denying others access to their spaces and resources, but also boundary maintenance, in which one sanctions other in-group members for not protecting the group's social space.
    By contrast, Black Americans may police boundaries in minor ways such as criticizing White Americans for tanning themselves to look more Black \parencite[pp.~15-16]{myers_race_2001}, but primarily Black Americans have access to the latter mechanism only because the racialized social system has already excluded them from having the power to control public spaces.
    One form this might take for White Americans is through parenting in which they, for example, allow their children to have Black friends at school but not to go to their homes or have romantic relationships with them \parencite{carter_racialization_2012}.
    Another form of boundary maintenance sees Black Americans criticizing other Black Americans for academic achievements under the belief that academia is a White space \parencite[p.~16]{brown_useful_2012}.\footnote{
      The oppositional culture theory this comes from has been generally rejected as an explanation for African-American educational achievement \parencite[p.~16]{brown_useful_2012}, but this does not mean that such discourse does not occur.
    } For a Black American to advance in their education is thus to abandon their peers and embrace the culture of their oppressors.
    % Relatedly, Whites who moved to predominantly Black schools in their early years have reported being readily accepted, whereas Blacks who moved to predominantly White schools were ostracized (S. Carter et al. 2012)
      % Essentially, there was no reason to ostracize the White students in the Black schools because there is not a sense built into society that school is the domain of Blacks, whereas Whites may feel like their space is being invaded when Black students arrive

    % Racialized people are uneasy with labeling their identities
      % Becker's (2014) participant did not want to use the word African-American because it was reductive (i.e., African is a large continent with many cultures) (47)

    Boundary marking, policing, and maintenance take on certain characteristics when used to produce and reproduce racialization in discourse.
    Once groups are identified, they are then characterized in ways to construct a hierarchy of humanization.
    This hierarchy is then defended on both sides, although the means of doing so is different for the groups involved.
    Thsoe at the top of the hierarchy have the power to police boundaries, whereas the marginalized can only effectively carry out boundary maintenance.
    The following research question for this chapter therefore aims to search for signs of this same logic in the discourse of Creoles and Cajuns.

    \begin{itemize}
      \item[RQ3:] Is the discourse of Creoles and Cajuns in Louisiana indicative of the racialization of these groups in that it creates, polices, and maintains inequal boundaries?
    \end{itemize}

    \subsection{Racializing discourse in Louisiana}
      While this question has not been taken up before in the literature on Creoles and Cajuns, \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) work contains enlightening discourse data that can be re-examined from the angle of racialization.
      Wendte himself had the goal of qualitatively looking into how Texan and Louisianian Creoles who speak F\&C define what being Creole means to them.
      Importantly, he did not include Cajuns as primary participants, though he did report on some who insisted on being interviewed anyway.
      This limited the ability to speak about outgroup characterizations of Creoles.

      % Boundary marking
      Boundary marking can be found throughout \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) data.
      This took various forms such as associating different yet related cultural practices -- zydeco versus Cajun music (pp.~139/207-208/211), spice levels in cooking (pp.~143/215) -- to each group, often exaggerating the differences in these practices, as well as contesting the meaning and associations surround terms taken pejoratively at times (pp.~190-191).
      As in the data for the present study, it was also clear that fractal recursivity played a role in both marking boundaries and characterizing those on either side of those boundaries (pp.~168/179/181-184/188-191/200-201/218-219/275-279/284-275/297-298).
      Fractal recursivity involves transferring a distinction at one level of social structure to another level \parencite[p.~38]{irvine_language_2000}, in this case transferring the non-White and White distinction of the broader US to the categories of Creole and Cajun in Louisiana, respectively.

      % "Others" are not good
        % Others can be a specific form of oneself
          % A woman from rural Evangeline Parish, she was herself Creole but a Creole who was ``plus cadien'' \gloss{more Cajun} (p.~275).
            % She appeared to mean that she was specifically not Black, describing herself instead as a mix of Spanish, European, and Native America, whereas others who call themselves Creoles were additionally Black (pp.~280-281).
            % In each of these groups, she rather bluntly explained that it was not good to mix with Blacks and expressed consternation at sometimes being labeled Black on official documents.
            % These statements implicitly acknowledged the widespread idea that Cajun is White and Creole is Black as this woman struggled to shed herself of the stigma of being considered Black and align herself instead with Whites to such an extent that she seemed to harbor a racist ideology even against herself as, during these exchanges, she presented Wendte with a DNA test she had done that showed that she had African ancestors.

      % Boundary maintenance
      Boundary maintenance was carried out primarily in two ways in \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) data.
      One was to downplay some of the above boundary marking mechanisms and instead associate being Creole with simply being a good and resourceful person (pp.~136/205).
      These positive traits appeared to be meant to entice would-be Creoles to embrace the category.
      Additionally, Creoles sometimes spoke about the need to remain closely associated with Louisiana and with F\&C.
      Those who migrated to Texas put at risk their ability to identify as Creole as did those who no longer engaged in cultural practices associated with Louisiana or who lost their ability to speak F\&C either completely or not well enough (pp.~133-135/137/146-147/153-155/202-203/224-225/227-228/230-232/289).

        % Don't move away from LA or abandon the language or you may no longer be Creole

      % Boundary policing
      One way in which boundary policing can take place in a racialized social system is by placing the burden of learning a standard language variety on those who have been marginalized.
      This complicated when considering F\&C as this is now something of a heritage language, but \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) data did still demonstrate similar language ideology at play, expressed in terms of the belief that Cajun speak F\&C better than Creoles (p.~176).
      This sentiment was even repeated by a Creole women who herself used all Cajun-marked subject pronouns (p.~255).

      Clearer examples of boundary policing came under the form of differing levels of restrictions on who could claim Cajun identity versus who could claim Creole identity.
      The former plainly required one to be able to say that they are also White (pp.~296-297).
      The complete absence of anyone attempting to override this requirement among the Louisiana participants suggests that this restriction is thoroughly enforced.
      On the other hand, Creole identity was open to to almost anyone even though it was generally those who could not claim a White identity who identified as Creole.
      A striking example of this came when two participants identified as White Cajuns except in the presence of a Black friend, at which point they identified as Creoles.
      When this Black friend was in their company, she looked to them for permission to claim Creole as her identity when asked and denied that she could claim a Cajun identity, too, like her friends did (pp.~293-294).
      In this case, Cajuns were not only policing the boundaries of Cajunness but also the boundaries of Creoleness.

      % Cajuns can even police who is allowed to be Creole
        % Finally, \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) Louisiana data suggested that there is a restriction to who can self-identify as a Cajun, higher in the racial hierarchy, that does not exist for identifying as a Creole.
        % The restriction for Cajun self-identification that was expressed was that one must be White to be Cajun (pp.~296-297).
        % A few Louisianian Creoles did initially try to say that Cajuns can be various colors but then always went on to imply that Cajuns were White or close to White (pp.~295-296).
        % For Creoles, however, the barrier to entry was signficantly more flexible.
        % At one point, a participant told Wendte that he himself could ``qualifier pour un Créole'' \gloss{qualify as a Creole} despite Wendte being a White non-Louisianian and non-native speaker of F\&C (p.~235).
        % The openness of the category was particularly true for those who understood it in the original sense as being no more than native to Louisiana.
        % Three participants from Ville Platte in Evangeline Parish had recently re-identified as Creole after learning this, whereas they spent their lives identifying as Cajun to avoid being considered Black if they had tried to identify as Creole (pp.~282-283).
        % This freedom then, was seen as effectively given to Whites but not non-Whites, and it was a freedom that could be fluid.
        % Two other participants from rural Evangeline Parish were reported identifying as White Cajuns except in the presence of a Black friend, at which point they identified as Creoles.
        % Additionally, this Black friend from Saint Landry Parish, while in their company, defined Cajuns as Frenchmen instead of White then claimed to not know her own identity when asked.
        % Instead, she looked to the other two for permission to identify as Creole and denied that she could be Cajun, as well, like her friends (pp.~293-294).
        % This is reminiscent of the communicative rules of \foreign{de jure} segregation that \textcite{morgan_more_2022} discussed where permission to speak is required for racialized people and where they were expected to say only what those of higher racial status wanted them to say, in this case even to the extent where the individual in the group who much more clearly could lay claim to being Creole did not feel comfortable doing so in front of Whites who were allowed to freely claim whatever identity they wanted.

      \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) work, despite not attempting to address race, still suggested that Creoles and Cajuns mark, police, and maintain boundaries for these two categories in their discourse much as Americans do for White and non-White categories broadly in the US.
      It was thus expected that the discourse data from the present study would be even more elucidating into how this is carried out given the addition of Cajun voices as well as focusing conversations on race when possible.

  \section{Analysis}
    \label{sec:discourse_analysis}
    Evidence of the racialization of Creoles and Cajuns was found in the discourse of these groups in F\&C.
    Boundaries for both groups were marked, but those markings were different for each in ways that are consistent with racial hierarchies.
    Strategies for policing and maintaining those boundaries also resembled what is found in racializied social systems. % Might need to add hedge that there wasn't much of either going on.
    Two of the primary questions posed to participants asked what a Creole is and what a Cajun is in participants' personal views, essentially questions aimed at asking participants to conduct boundary marking, and so this section is organized along those lines.

    % The discourse of participants in this study suggests in many ways that Creoles have been racialized.
    % In speaking of language, Creole-marked pronouns are consciously associated with Creoles and Cajun-marked pronouns with Cajuns.
    % Stigma is also attached to those Creole speech patterns in very explicit ways.
    % When defining what makes one a Cajun, race becomes fairly invisible.
    % Factors generally include Acadian ancestry and cultural practices but not passing as White despite the latter being the strictest condition.
    % In contrast, Creole is regularly equated to being Black despite this category being historically more open, a fact that many participants were aware of to at least some degree.
    % Finally, while Creoles' and Cajuns' life experiences showed some similarities, the former often found themselves in lower status positions and were much more likely to be able to relate personal experiences of discrimination.
    
    \subsection{Marking the boundaries of Cajunness}
      \label{sec:what_cajun}
      When participants were asked what a Cajun is, they focused considerable attention on ancestry.
      However, this was not treated in terms of the racialized social categories of the broader US as was done for Creoles.
      Cajun identity had the privilege of being conceptualized as racially neutral where Acadian ancestry and cultural practices were highlighted rather than essentialist characteristics and discrimination.

      \subsubsection{Cajun ancestry}
        Acadians themselves were French-speaking colonists of the Maritime provinces in Canada whose descendants reside largely in the Maritimes and Louisiana today.
        When asked what a Cajun is, participants, especially Cajuns, were often quick and succinct in responding that Cajuns are descendants of Acadians as in Sentences \ref{sent:cajun_lesage} through \ref{sent:cajun_floyd}.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          % \item Brian (Cajun): Moi, je dis un Cadien, c'est du monde qui a venu de Canada. (48:14) \label{sent:cajun_brian}
          % \item[] \longtrans{Brian (Cajun): Me, I say a Cajun, that's people who came from Canada.}
          \item Oliver L. (Cajun): Cadien, c'est surtout quelqu'un qui est venu avec le groupe des Acadiens après la dispersion des Acadiens du Canada. (65:44) \label{sent:cajun_lesage}
          \item[] \longtrans{Oliver L. (Cajun): Cajun, that's especially someone who came with the group of Acadians after the dispersion of the Acadians from Canada.}
          \item Arthur (Cajun): C'est des personnes que le histoire, le généologie vient de le Nouvelle-Écosse. (41:09) \label{sent:cajun_arthur}
          \item[] \longtrans{Arthur (Cajun): It's people whose history, geneology come from Nova Scotia.}
        \end{enumerate}
        The above two examples highlighted Canada and Nova Scotia as the starting place of Acadians, but Acadia was also referenced.
        Creoles expressed this idea in this same matter of fact way, as well, as in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_jerry} and in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_floyd}.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Jerry (White Creole): Un Cadien? Well, le monde vient de Acadie. (31:56) \label{sent:cajun_jerry}
          \item[] \longtrans{Jerry (White Creole): A Cajun? Well, the people who came from Acadia.}
          \item Floyd (Creole): Comme mo mo tais lire, les Cadiens taient sortis dans Canada. (51:48) \label{sent:cajun_floyd}
          \item[] \longtrans{Floyd (Creole): As I was reading, Cajuns had come out of Canada.}
        \end{enumerate}

        % Brian Roger
          % (48:14) [from Canada]
