        % Dennis Oubre
          % (24:09)
          % Dennis (Cajun): Le définition, y a à peu près cinq millions descendants de les premiers Acadiens qu'a établi le colonie Acadie qui s'appelle aujourd'hui la Nouvelle-Écosse, mais les seuls groupes que ç'appelle les Cadiens, c'est eux qu'étaient ici en Louisiane.

        For one participant, the hardships that the Acadians endured when they were expelled from Canada were enough to suggest that they, and by extension Cajuns, are a race.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Judy (Cajun): Well, moi je crois, tu connais, we're a race. (61:37) \label{sent:cajun_judy1}
          \item[] \longtrans{Judy (Cajun): Well, I believe, you know, we're a race.}
        \end{enumerate}
        For Judy, this made it something of a necessity to have Acadian ancestry if one wished to claim a Cajun identity, presumably because to do otherwise would be to dishonor the hardships of the Acadians.
        This idea that Acadian/Cajun is racialized to the lower end of a racial hierarchy is perhaps not far off historically in the sense that Acadians may have been dehumanized in order to justify their expulsion to take their land, after which they faced discrimination wherever they tried to go.
        More recently, the comments of Creoles who suggest that Cajun was a derogatory term in the not so distant past further supports the view of Cajun as a race.
        However, any historical racialization of Acadians in the Maritimes or stigmatizion of Cajuns before 1960 does not necessarily entail a modern day marginalization of Cajuns in Louisiana.
        
        % Randal Chenevert
          % (50:55) [when asked, highlights Acadian ancestry but doesn't say what to do with others]
          % Randal (Cajun): Un Cadien, c'est quelqu'un, je peux pas dire que faut tu d'être acadien pour d'être acadien, c'est pas nécessaire, mais un tas de Cadiens, ils étaient des Acadiens.

        % The story of how the word Cajun was derived is often shared
          % Dennis Oubre
            % (24:30)
            % Dennis (Cajun): Et quand ils sont arrivés, ils ont présenté comme, "Nous sommes des Acadiens," et les Espagnols et le monde à Nouvelle-Orléans avaient du tracas à dire Acadien, ça fait ça disait Cadien.
          % Jerry Pierre Quintero
            % (32:07) [immediately after giving an Acadian definition of Cajuns]
            % JPQ: Et là, c'est durant ici quand ils estiont devenus acadiens, le mot a devenu cadien.
          % Laura Laviolette
            % (56:10) [while giving alter ethnicities]
            % Laura (Cajun): On est tous cadiens, mais c'est acadienne. Oui, ça a juste coupé ça.
          % Arthur Rousseau
            % (42:30)
            % Arthur (Cajun): Le nom de les personnes, c'était cadien, like Acadian, cadien, Cajun. It's a corruption of the word. C'est pas épelé correctement -- c'est C A J I N suppose être -- mais les personnes d'autres places savaient ainsi, "Vouz-aut est un, vouz êt- vouz est un Cajun?" "Non, ch'sus pas un Cajun. Ch'sus un Cadien."

        Nuances in how Cajun boundaries were marked, as well as when and how they were maintained and policed, were often brought out when eliciting the ethnicities of participants' alters, where the real world application of their definitions of Cajuns naturally ran into contradictions.
        That is not to say that no alters were classified as Cajun according to ancestry.
        Family names were a common tool used for choosing alter ethnicities, as in Sentences \ref{sent:cajun_cynthia1} through \ref{sent:cajun_jack}.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Cynthia (Cajun): Oh ouais ouais. Son nom de famille, c'est Thibodeaux. C'est beaucoup cadien, ça. (60:11) \label{sent:cajun_cynthia1}
          \item[] \longtrans{Cynthia (Cajun): Oh yeah yeah. His family name, that's Thibodeaux. That's very Cajun, that.}
          \item Randal (Cajun): Oh, Huey est cadien, oh, haha, yeah. Il est un Mabile. (48:17) \label{sent:cajun_randal1}
          \item[] \longtrans{Randal (Cajun): Oh, Huey is Cajun, oh, haha, yeah. He's a Mabile.}
          \item Jack (Cajun): Wilton, il est cadien. Il est Chenevert. Chenevert, c'est un mot très très cadien. (54:17) \label{sent:cajun_jack}
          \item[] \longtrans{Jack (Cajun): Wilton, he's Cajun. He's a Chenevert. Chenevert, that's a very very Cajun word.}
        \end{enumerate}
        These three examples were particularly emphatic about just how Cajun these last names were.
        In this case, Chenevert is notable.
        This was the family name of two participants in this study: Randal, a White Cajun, and Rachel, a Black Creole.
        Despite how strongly linked Jack considered Chenevert to be to Cajun ancestry, it is highly unlikely that Rachel could have passed as Cajun because she would certainly not have been able to pass as White.

        % Austin Roy
          % (71:55)
          % Austin (Cajun): Moi, je dirais que c'est un Cadien. C'est un Chretien d'Arnaudville.
        % Bruce Wiltz
          % (45:58)
          % Bruce (Cajun): Ça s'appelle tous des Cadiens, et je connais Poursine, c'est acadien.
        % Elizabeth Naquin
          % (50:14) [not just an Italian family name but doesn't speak French]
          % EN: Geraldine, pas cadienne. Marks. Li était élevée à Crowley. Ses parents c'était pas, c'était Italian. Okay. Marks is her maiden name. Mo crois pas li parle français.

        % There would sometimes be some hesitancy that usually resolved in explaining that the alter would certainly call themselves Cajun
          % Bruce Wiltz
            % (46:03)
            % Bruce (Cajun): Travis Periou though, c'est pas acadien. Je crois pas, mais le nom de famille de sa mère, c'était Prince, ça fait sais pas c'était ... Mais oui, il a été élevé avec nous ici. C'était, ouais ouais, ils ont dit il est cadien, eh, et lui, il disait il était cadien.

        The contradiction made by having an Acadian family name and not being able to pass as White did not come up explicitly, and so no explicit boundary policing was enacted with respect to such individuals.
        What did come up, however, was that many Cajuns do not in fact have Acadian family names.
        In Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_randal2}, Randal acknowledged this while trying to decide the ethnicity of his wife.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Randal (Cajun): Son nom de famille, c'est Saint Amant. Ça c'est espagnol, mais comme un tas des noms, y a des Allemands, y a des Espagnols ici qui parlent français qui considéraient des Cadiens, ça fait elle a, tu peux dire espagnole, mais elle est cadien. (47:15) \label{sent:cajun_randal2}
          \item[] \longtrans{Randal (Cajun): Her family name, that's Saint Amant. That's Spanish, but like a lot of names, there are Germans, there are Spanish people here who speak French who would consider themselves Cajun, so she, you can say Spanish, but she's Cajun.}
        \end{enumerate}
        Importantly, the national origins he gave for family names of Cajuns were all European, and Europeanness is what White stands for in the racialized social system of the broader US.
        Taking Cajun to be a local form of White, it was thus not important to deny those with non-Acadian European ancestors from crossing into the boundary of Cajun.
        Lillian was more explicit about this in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_lillian1} where she acknowledged that her husband was White, which helped his case for saying that he was Cajun despite his German family name.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Lillian (Cajun): Il est allemand, mais il est blanc, mais il parle cadien. Il dit, je crois lui il dit il est cadien, mais il connaît son ancêtres sont allemands. (39:13) \label{sent:cajun_lillian1}
          \item[] \longtrans{Lillian (Cajun): He's German, but he's White, but he speaks Cajun. He says, I believe that he says that he's Cajun, but he knows that his ancestors are German.}
        \end{enumerate}
        Dennis also focused on Cajuns with German family names in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_dennis1}.
        In his case, however, the boundaries of Cajun identity did not extend to just any European descendents in Louisiana but more specifically to those whose ancestors had integrated with Acadians in some way.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Dennis (Cajun): Ça fait, y a toujours des vieilles familles de l'Allemand -- Comardelle, D'Entremont, Lachaussee, Bogard -- mais ils ont tous appris français. Ils ont marié les Acadiens. Aujourd'hui, ça croit c'est tous des Acadiens. (23:28) \label{sent:cajun_dennis1}
          \item[] \longtrans{Dennis (Cajun): So, there are still old families from Germany -- Comardelle, D'Entremont, Lachaussee, Bogard -- but they have all learned French. They married Acadians. Today, they believe that they're all Acadians.}
        \end{enumerate}
        Like Lillian, he also brought up the ability to speak French, or ``Cajun'' in Lillian's case, drawing the association between Cajuns and a way of speaking.
        What was not brought up by Cajuns in this discussion was what Terry brought up in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_terry}.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Terry (Creole): Ina un tas de ces Cadiens-là qui va pas dire ils ont du sang sauvage, mais ina z-en qui est mêlés. (45:12) \label{sent:cajun_terry}
          \item[] \longtrans{Terry (Creole): There are a lot of these Cajuns who won't say that they have some savage [Indian] blood, but there are some who are mixed.}
        \end{enumerate}
        Terry, who had spoken at length about Creoles mixing with Indians, explained that Cajuns also mixed with Indians despite Cajuns not wanting to say so.
        The reluctance to do so would of course be natural in this racialized social system.
        Indians are not European and so not White and so cannot be Cajun in the views of Cajuns themselves.
        Indeed, fundamental to studies of language variation in F\&C in the parishes of Terrebonne and Lafourche where Indians are far more numerous was the division between Indians and Cajuns \parencite{dajko_ethnic_2009, rottet_language_1995}
        As a Creole, though, Terry was able to contest this marking of the boundary.
        
        % Arthur Rousseau
          % (42:05) [these days, it's not just ancestry]
          % Arthur (Cajun): Mais, dans ce temps-ici, Cajun est populai[ʁ]e, et y a beaucoup des gens avec, comme Oliver. Oliver, il est Gomez, mais son nom est espagnol, mais ch'pense i dit il est cadien.
        % Brian Roger
          % (82:54) [giving the ethnicities of his alters]
          % Brian (Cajun): D'après moi, ils sont proche tous cadiens, mais ina un tas de Arnaudville, ina plusieurs des Allemands, de familles allemands qui a venu. Par exemple, Martha, son dernier nom avant elle s'a marié c'était Abribat. C'est allemand, un nom allemand.
          % (90:00) [remarking on Cajun geneologies]
          % Brian (Cajun): Ça fait, c'est dur à être un Cadien pur.
        % Dennis Oubre
          % (24:14)
          % Dennis (Cajun): Y a personne en vie personne qu'a tous les ancêtres de là-bas [Acadia].
        % Elizabeth Naquin
          % (51:10) [acknowledging a non-French ancestry]
          % EN: Brian cadien. Cadien, mais avec un nom espagnol.
        % Lucille Royer
          % (31:23)
          % Lucille (Cajun): Je me considère cadienne, parce que mes parents parlaient pas anglais, mais mon nom de famille, Royer, c'est pas un nom acadien.
            % She went on to say her mother's family name was possibly Irish, and her father's family was directly from France.
        % Oliver Gomez
          % (3:00)
          % Oliver G. (Cajun): Mon nom est Oliver Gomez. Ça c'est un bon nom cadien, parce que les Espagnols a venu à Nouvelle-Ibérie.
        % Lillian Himel
          % (1:02) [talking about her maiden name in contrast to her German-origin married name]
          % Lillian (Cajun): Miller.
          % Joshua (Interviewer): Miller, okay. Ça c'est plutôt français, ouais.
          % Lillian (Cajun): Ouais ouais, c'est français, et mes grands-parents, c'était deux Pinel, un Mabile, et Miller, ça fait je dis que je suis cent pour cent cadien.
          % (43:58) [talking about how there are Cajuns with German, Spanish, Italian ancestors]
          % Lillian (Cajun): Ça fait, pour moi, cadien, c'est quelqu'un qu'était élevé ici, et si ça parle cadien, c'est plus cadien.
            % On its face, this is all inclusive, but it is unlikely that she was including anyone who can't pass for White.
            % She went on to discuss how everyone was intermarried.

        % Especially if they marry in
          % Brian Roger
            % (2:15) [acknowledging that his family isn't purely from Acadia but rather married in]
            % Brian (Cajun): Le premier Roger venait de une île en-dedans le Mediterranean, Menorca. Ça fait, lui, il a joint sa femme en-dedans Maryland. Elle, elle viensait de Canada.
              % He later highlighted that the wife was a Chenevert (3:37), which was described as a very Acadian name by Jack, which all again shows the importance of family names.
          % Bruce Wiltz
            % (32:35) [his Wiltz ancestor came directly from France]
            % Bruce (Cajun): Le premier Wiltz, il est pas acadien, eh. Lui, il est devenu directement de la France quand il avait, je crois, quinze ans, ... directement vers la Nouvelle-Orléans, ... mais la mère à mon père, c'était un Pinel. C'est acadien. [went on to describe how all the others in that line were Acadian]
          % Cynthia Robichaux Savoie
            % (38:16) [asked what a Cajun is]
            % Cynthia (Cajun): Moi, je suis cadienne, parce que ma famille est cadienne, mais il y a du monde d'ailleurs, comme on dit 'les Américains', quelqu'un qui n'est pas cadien qu'a marié un Cadien, et il commence à s'appeler cadien.

      \subsubsection{Cajun language}
        As Lillian and Dennis made clear above, speaking F\&C can help one claim a Cajun identity and so can be said to do significant work in marking the boundaries of Cajunness.
        This was brought up again and again when working through the ethnicities of alters.
        Although policing of boundaries was rare due to discourse data being derived from one on one views with myself rather than with people who would be targets of policing, this process of characterizing alters did bring up some indications of how that policing would play out.
        For Bruce, the first thing he considered when thinking about the ethnicity of his alter in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_bruce} was how this alter learned F\&C.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Bruce (Cajun): Dubois, Gilroy Dubois. Oui, je crois il a appris, je suis pas sûr à quel âge il allait, et c'était comme ça avec Jack. Il dit, lui, il a appris le français avec ses grands-parents. (47:15) \label{sent:cajun_bruce}
          \item[] \longtrans{Bruce (Cajun): Dubois, Gilroy Dubois. Yes, I believe that he learned, I'm not sure at what age he was going, and it was like that with Jack. He says that he learned French with his grandparents.}
        \end{enumerate}
        For Rose in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_rose}, even being anglophone but sending one's children to French immersion schooling showed enough appreciation for F\&C for her daughter to be able to qualify as Cajun.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Rose (Cajun): Out of the three, she, yeah, she's my strongest one, yeah because she sends her kids to French immersion. That says it all. (100:54) \label{sent:cajun_rose}
        \end{enumerate}
        Rose's daughter was in fact present during the interview and could mostly understand F\&C but did not produce it.
        This receptive knowledge and the fact that she demonstrated an appreciation for F\&C was enough to not require policing her relative to the Cajun boundary.
        Likewise on the other side of the boundary, receptive bilingualism was sufficient for at least one Louisianian Creole in \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) data to accept others as Creole (p.~225).

        Austin went even further with this idea.
        Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_austin1} shows him making a language exception so that he could classify each of his anglophone brothers as Cajun, albeit ``américanisé'' \gloss{Americanized}, despite his own explicit definition for Cajuns being White speakers of F\&C.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Austin (Cajun): L'affaire c'est que, si tout quelqu'un que je connais aurait été nés cent années passées, le monde qui s'intéresse pas au langage et tout ça, ça parlerait le français. \label{sent:cajun_austin1}
          \item[] \longtrans{Austin (Cajun): The thing is that, if everyone that I know would have been born one hundred years ago, the people who aren't interested in language and all that, they would speak French.}
        \end{enumerate}
        In effect, anyone in Louisiana whose ancestors were also in Louisiana could fit within the Cajun boundaries.
        What he did not address, however, was that this exception would allow almost all White-passing South Louisianians to identify as Cajun, the majority of whom are not even receptively bilingual in F\&C but simply anglophone.
        While language still retained some importance for Austin, in practice, it could be heavily de-emphasized without impacted the boundaries of Cajunness.
        % Wendte
          % Learning standard variety
            % The burdern of racialized people being tasked with learning a standard language variety is complicated for F\&C speakers as this is now something of a heritage language.
            % \textcite{wendte_tale_2020} quoted a number of Creoles both in Texas and Louisiana highlighting that being able to speak Creole is important for being Creole (pp.~146-147/153-155/202/224-225/230-232/289).
            % What they did not highlight was a need to learn a prestigious variety of F\&C, although it is also important to note that many of the participants used Cajun-marked subject pronouns and still called their language Creole, so these participants could be said to already be speaking the prestigious local variety.
            % That said, many still expressed the belief that Cajuns/Whites speak better than Creoles (p.~176).
            % One striking example of how this played out was when a women from Saint Landry Parish who considered herself to be Black and used all Cajun-marked subject pronouns still expressed the belief that Cajuns spoke better than people like herself (p.~255).
            % Racialization was such a strong factor in her mind that she believed that she spoke worse than others whose speech patterns she actually shared simply because she was lower in the racial hierarchy.

        % Speaking F&C was often invoked, particularly when thinking out loud about the ethnicities of alters
          % Jack Munson
            % (37:21) [added immediately after his Acadian definition of Cajuns]
            % Jack (Cajun): Y a beaucoup du monde qu'était pas cadien. ... They became acculturated to the Cajun language, et they were Spanish ici, en espagnol, ça fait y a beaucoup des Espagnols. ... Et ça parle le cadien.
          % Deborah Tauzin
            % (72:15) [her son is American because he doesn't speak French]
            % Joshua (Interviewer): Par exemple, pour Travis, est-ce qu'il est cadien, créole, américain?
            % Deborah (White Creole): Non, américain, américain. Il parle pas français.
              % It is not clear whether she was saying that he could not be Cajun because of language or could not be Creole, but notably she was a White Creole. Language is perhaps a qualifier only for those who identify as White given that no non-White Creoles brought it up and no Cajuns were non-White.
      
      \subsubsection{Cajun culture}
        Setting the boundaries for Cajun identity using culture would naturally run into the same problem that Austin's focus on language did if held as necessary and sufficient conditions.
        However, many participants did in fact define Cajuns by describing their culture and did so without requiring a strict adherence to that culture in order to be Cajun.
        Dennis implicated religion as helping to mark the boundaries of Cajunness in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_dennis2}, but more so he stressed the idea that Cajuns are accepting of others.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Dennis (Cajun): Tu peux dire c'est un culture. C'est acceptance de une manière de vivre, de regarder la vie, regarder les hommes, regarder le bon Dieu. (26:31) \label{sent:cajun_dennis2}
          \item[] \longtrans{Dennis (Cajun): You can say that it's a culture. It's being accepting of a way of living, of looking at life, regarding man, regarding the good Lord.}
        \end{enumerate}
        Randal spoke in similarly general terms in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_randal3} with the addition of suggesting the hardworking nature of Cajuns as well as differences in cooking.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Randal (Cajun): C'est leur manière de vivre, culture, langage, la manière on cuit. Moi, je cuis juste pareil comme mes parents et mes grands-parents. ... Le manière de penser pour leur job, et puis pas peur de se saler à travailler, aider à tout le monde que tu peux. (51:13) \label{sent:cajun_randal3}
          \item[] \longtrans{Randal (Cajun): It's their way of living, culture, language, the way we cook. Me, I cook just like my parents and my grandparents. ... The way of thinking about their job, and then not fearing getting dirty at work, helping everyone that you can.}
        \end{enumerate}
        The topic of cooking will be discussed more in detail in Section \ref{sec:what_creole} as this is a particularly salient point of distinction between Cajuns and Creoles.
        In Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_steven}, Steven was discussing hunting woodcocks, and in doing so, implied that Cajuns are avid hunters.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Steven (Cajun): Ina pas trop qui restent parce que les Cadiens a tué tout. (23:05) \label{sent:cajun_steven}
          \item[] \longtrans{Steven (Cajun) There aren't too many that remain because the Cajuns killed everything.}
        \end{enumerate}
        None of these are cultural traits or activities that are particularly unique to Cajuns.
        Creoles as well highlighted positive traits like being hardworking and accepting of others.
        Even when it comes to cooking, Creole dishes that Cajuns can name are generally the same as Cajun dishes with only vaguely identifiable differences.
        
        A more notable statement about culture came from Judy in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_judy2}.
        Judy was speaking about where brown cotton has been used in South Louisiana for blankets and two of the parishes she named were Saint Landry and Saint Martin where many Creoles live, so I had inquired about whether Creoles had taken up what she was describing as an Acadian practice.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item[] Judy (Cajun): J'ai jamais jamais trouvé une couverte que quelqu'un de la couleur noire a fait, et je peux pas comprendre pourquoi. Ils étaient après vivre avec nous-autres. We were friendly with the Blacks. (51:17) \label{sent:cajun_judy2}
          \item[] \longtrans{Judy (Cajun): I never never found a blanket that a someone Black made, and I can't understand why. They were living with us. We were friendly with the Blacks.}
        \end{enumerate}
        First, she made the connection between Creoles and being Black once again as I asked explicitly about ``Créoles'' whereas she responded by referring to Black people.
        Second, she expressed confusion over Creoles not taking up the practice due to how closely Cajuns and Creoles lived together, as if the boundaries between the two groups were rather porous.
        However, as she went on to discuss an example of that closeness, it was clear that the Creole man she was describing held a much lower status than the White family with whom he interacted.
        In the example, the Creole man was required to walk through the back door of the house that held his deceased White friend's coffin, implying clear expectations of segregation.
        In racialized social systems, physical closeness and regularity of interaction do not necessarily entail the sort of social closeness needed for certain forms of cultural diffusion.

        % Bruce Wiltz
          % (34:50) [explaining how the emphasis on Acadian origins diminished]
          % Bruce (Cajun): Ça a devenu que c'était peut-être la joie de vivre ici, ...  si t'as t'as été élevé ici. Ça s'appelle les Cadiens, eh?
        % Cynthia Robichaux Savoie
          % (23:25) She related a story of how her husband, a Cajun, introduced a French national who was staying with them to a French stranger while they were out and how he was confused that they didn't really talk, because for him, Cajuns in the same situation would end up getting so chummy that they have dinner together.
          % (24:48)
          % Cynthia (Cajun): Si ç'aurait été deux Cadiens à Paris, je te promets, ils auraient trouvé un cousin en commun, et puis ils auraient soupé ensemble.
        % Errol Stoufle
          % (30:11) [when asked what a Cajun is, equates it to nothing more than "a culture"]
          % Errol (Cajun): Mo mo étais crois c'est juste un slang pour, you know, une culture, tu connais? Le monde qui parle français, yé parlent un certain langage, tu connais?
        % Lucille Royer
          % (33:07) [highlighting just how important French is for identifying as Cajun for her]
          % Lucille (Cajun): Tu peux te dire cadien autant que tu veux, mais si tu possèdes pas la langue, t'es pas vraiment cadien.

        Further complicating the use of cultural products and practices for marking Cajun boundaries is that Cajun has become something of a catch-all term in South Louisiana for all local cultural products or practices.
        This had perhaps not happened yet by the 1960s as Mary explained in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_mary} that Cajun music was not what her and her fellow LSU students wanted to dance to at that time.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Mary (Cajun): Oh non non non non. C'était les années soixante, et personne à Bâton-Rouge embrassait le cadienisme, eh? (23:08) \label{sent:cajun_mary}
          \item[] \longtrans{Cynthia (Cajun): Oh no no no no. That was the sixties, and no one in Baton Rouge was embracing Cajunism, eh?}
        \end{enumerate}
        Describing local music as Cajun -- or language as Cajun -- was not done during the youths of some participants, as Lucille explained in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_lucille}.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Lucille (Cajun): Y avait pas de français cadien ou créole. Y avait le français. C'était la musique en français. C'était pas la musique cadienne, you know? (40:16) \label{sent:cajun_lucille}
          \item[] \longtrans{Lucille (Cajun): There was no Cajun or Creole French. There was French. It was music in French. It wasn't Cajun music, you know?}
        \end{enumerate}
        Instead of using the Cajun as a general descriptor, the term French was used.
        However, as Sentences \ref{sent:cajun_dennis3} and \ref{sent:cajun_lillian2} show, anything from college football teams to beach resorts to the local accordeon music that was previously called French music has come to be labeled Cajun today.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Dennis (Cajun): Tu peux aller au université ici, va d'être un Raging Cajun. \label{sent:cajun_dennis3}
          \item[] \longtrans{Dennis (Cajun): You can go to the university here, go be a Raging Cajun\footnote{
            Raging Cajuns is the name of the university's football team.
          }.}
          \item Lillian (Cajun): Tu connais où Holly Beach? C'est le Cajun Riviera. \label{sent:cajun_lillian2}
          \item[] \longtrans{Lillian (Cajun): You know where Holly Beach is? That's the Cajun Riviera.}
        \end{enumerate}
        This has been so pervasive that Deborah expressed a distaste for the term in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_deborah} at least in part because of its ever-presence.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Deborah (White Creole): Je préfère créole que cadien. ... Non, j'aime pas beaucoup de Cajun. C'est bon. C'est okay, mais it's, c'est, on va dire en anglais a catch word. Cajun, Cajun food, Cajun dances, Cajun music, you know? \label{sent:cajun_deborah}
          \item[] \longtrans{Deborah (White Creole): I prefere Creole to Cajun. ... No, I don't much like Cajun. It's okay. It's okay, but it's, it's, we will say in English a catch word. Cajun, Cajun food, Cajun dances, Cajun music, you know?}
        \end{enumerate}
        It is important to remember in all of this that the social category that has historically been more inclusive has been Creole, and in fact much of what is described as culturally Cajun is just as much culturally Creole, yet the racialization of the term Creole as lesser makes it a poorer candidate for marketing than Cajun.
        Cajun being the default racial category of South Louisiana, the local form of White, makes it safe to use for all purposes and marks the public sphere as the bounds of Cajuns.
          
        % Errol Stoufle
          % (3:40) [local accordeon music is specifically Cajun, not "French music" or anything else]
          % Joshua (Interviewer): Comment vous appelez cette musique? C'est le musique cadienne ou?
          % Errol (Cajun): Oui, c'est la musique cadien.
          % Joshua (Interviewer): Parce que j'ai entendu une fois que y a du monde qui l'appelle la musique française.
          % Errol (Cajun): Ouais un tas des, vraiment, c'est la musique cadien, parce que c'est des Cadiens qui sur l'accordéon, tune y'apè chanter. C'était la musique, c'était au français le m- uh cadien, tu connais?
            % This is a specific example of the prominence given to cultural products being Cajun rather than French or Creole or anything else.
          % (31:52) [how popular it is call oneself Cajun to the point where people will fight about it]
          % Errol (Cajun): Tout quelqu'un croit yé cadiens. Yé yé commencé vini de abattre, tu connais?
        % Arthur Rousseau
          % (43:49)
          % Arthur (Cajun): Course I'm a Ragin' Ca[dʒ]un over here. I graduated from USL. [emphasized S]
        % Bruce Wiltz
          % (40:35) [Cajun was stigmatized but then suddenly became "cool"]
          % Bruce (Cajun): They didn't want to identify as Cajun. It wasn't cool then, you know? Then all the sudden it became cool, and everybody wants to be Cajun. Go figure.
        % Rose Louvière
          % (61:47) [says the same thing as Lucille when asked if she identifies as Cajun]
          % Rose (Cajun): Quand je suitais dans l'école, high school, navait pas de mot cadien ... On était juste français. C'était juste français jusqu'à that particular thing happened, and then it was easier to a say cadien than français or explain.
          % (63:51) [when asked if one needs to speak French to be Cajun]
          % Rose (Cajun): Plus asteur, parce que n'importe quand y a un nouveau business, ça mis, mais je suis pas sûr ça parle français, c'est juste bon business de mettre cadien, et probable une ou deux personnes dans la place parlaient un petit brin français.

      \subsubsection{Cajun race}
        While participants had much to say about what is Cajun and what a Cajun is, they rarely marked its boundaries by appealing to Whiteness.
        This was especially true for Cajuns themselves, among whom only Austin made that connection in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_austin2}.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Austin (Cajun): C'est une différence raciale entre cadien et créole. Ça c'est la définition que j'étais élevé avec. C'était les Français noirs c'est des Créoles, et les Français blancs c'est des Cadiens. (51:30) \label{sent:cajun_austin2}
          \item[] \longtrans{Austin (Cajun): It's a racial different between Cajun and Creole. That's the definition I was raised with. It was that Black French people are Creoles, and White French people are Cajuns.}
        \end{enumerate}
        For him the primary aspect of being Cajun or Creole was speaking F\&C, but after that, the distinction came down to whether one passed as White or Black, making one either Cajun or Creole, respectively.
        The other two participants who explicitly made this connection were both Creoles.
        In the case of Gene in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_gene}, his response was particularly matter of fact.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Gene (Creole): Un Cadien? That's a White man. (43:56) \label{sent:cajun_gene}
          \item[] \longtrans{Gene (Creole): A Cajun? That's a White man.}
          \item James (Creole): Les Cadiens, okay, c'est les Blancs. Ils ont d'héritage de Nova Scotia. (41:27) \label{sent:cajun_james}
          \item[] \longtrans{James (Creole): Cajuns okay, those are Whites. The have a heritage from Nova Scotia.}
        \end{enumerate}
        Gene went on to speak about the label in clearly racial terms, explaining that Cajun can be used as a derogatory word for a White person just as the N-word can be for a Black person.
        This expectation that Cajun can be a derogatory term was also expressed by one of the Texan Creoles in \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) data (p.~190), so the idea was not unique to Gene even though the above discussion shows that Cajun is certainly not derogatory in the views of Cajuns themselves even for those Cajuns who understood the Cajuns had been stigmatized in the past.
        Gene himself was one of the older participants, having been born in \Sexpr{participants[participants$Name == "Gene Delcambre", "Birth Year"]}, which is an equally plausible explanation for why he saw Cajun as derogatory as the explanation that Creoles see the term this way.

        % Laura Laviolette
          % (57:03) [somewhat supports that "cadien" is not quite as nice (or as correct?) to say as "acadien"]
          % Laura (Cajun): C'est plus bon dire Acadien que des Cadiens.
          % Steven Marcel
          % (54:58) [quickly says "cadien" for all of his alters but distinguishes one as "acadien" just as quickly due to being from and living in Canada]

      In general, the boundaries of Cajunness were marked in neutral terms.
      Cajuns are at least partially the descendants of Acadians who ended up in Louisiana or they are the accepting, hardworking people of South Louisiana with a rich culture of language, music, food, and so forth.
      These are all undoubtedly fair characterizations, but what they do not say is just as indicative of where Cajuns fit in the racialized social system of South Louisiana.
      The presumed neutrality of Cajun identity is an outcome of the group's privileged racial position as the default group.
      Effectively, discourse around Cajun identity marks it as a local form of White, and any local product or practice that one can be proud of is Cajun.

    \subsection{Marking the boundaries of Creoleness}
      \label{sec:what_creole}
      Examining how the community understands Creoles helps to understand how they understand Cajuns.
      There were in fact two Creoles who suggested that they have or might have Acadians in their ancestry, Deborah Tauzin and Samantha Primeaux, but only the former would have the option of identifying as Cajun, because only the former could pass as White.
      There was also one Creole with what had been described as a very Cajun name, Rachel Chenevert.
      It is possible that she also had Acadian ancestors, but it is just as possible that her ancestors received the name by being enslaved by Acadians.
      Either way, she would not be able to identify as Cajun today because she could not pass as White.
      There are also many Creoles who partake in what were described as Cajun cultural practices in Section \ref{sec:what_cajun}, but unless they can pass as White, they cannot identify as Cajun.
      One can say that Cajun and Creole are not mutually exclusive categories, but in practice, they are effectively mutually exclusive as the understanding of modern Creoles among the participants here almost always implicated being Black, a trait one must not have in order to be Cajun.

      Many participants indeed had an understanding that Creole has meant many different things over time.
      Jack Munson, a Cajun, gave a particularly detailed and mostly accurate picture of the whole gamut of definitions in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_jack}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Jack (Cajun): Dans le vieux temps, un Créole, c'était la première génération de le monde qui est venu de l'Europe qui était né en Louisiane. First generation, your Creoles, whether Spanish or French or German or anything else. Un Créole. Mais, plus tard, le monde qui est venu de Haïti à la Nouvelle-Orléans. C'était les Blancs qui est venus. Leurs esclaves, je pense, y en a qui est venus avec leurs esclaves. ... Ils s'appelaient des Créoles, et un Créole dans un temps, c'était quelqu'un un peu plus haut qu'un Cadien, mais après plusieurs années, créole, c'était quelqu'un qui était pas cadien, et souvent ils estiont, on dit, les nègres, les Noirs. Eux-autres, ça s'appelait des Créoles. Pourquoi pas? Mais plus que ça, je connais pas, un Créole c'est un mélangement de sang aussi, blanc ou espagnol ou noir. (38:54) \label{sent:creole_jack}
        \item[] \longtrans{Jack (Cajun): In the old days, a Creole, that was the first generation of people who came from Europe who were born in Louisiana. First generation, your Creoles, whether Spanish or French or German or anything else. A Creole. But, later, the people who came from Haiti to New Orleans. That was Whites who came. Their slaves, I think, there were some who came with their slaves. ... They called themselves Creoles, and a Creole at one time, that was someone a bit higher than a Cajun, but after several years, Creole, that was someone who wasn't Cajun, and often they were, we say, negros, Blacks. Them, they call themselves Creoles. Why not? But more than that, I don't know, a Creole is a mix of blood also, White or Spanish or Black.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Jack's understanding of Creole only loses accuracy in that the post-Civil War Creole myth discussed in Section \ref{sec:creole_history} is sewn into his descriptions.
      For instance, anything and anyone from the colony that is now Louisiana was Creole, not only those whose ancestors were European.
      Also notable is that being Black or having Black ancestors, along with the essentialism of contextualizing this through blood, was brought into the picture.
      This was regularly the case when speaking about Creoles even though it almost never happened when participants spoke about Cajuns.
      % Wendte
        % The other exception was a Texan Creole speaking about his encounter with the word \lexi{nègre} when speaking to a Louisianian.
            % The former only understood the term as a racial slur, whereas the latter claimed to be using it as a term of endearment (pp.~190-191).
        % In Wendte's (2020) data, 3 pseudo-participants who were White Cajuns commented on the word nègre (305)
          % SM1 and VM1 showed "ambivalence" towards them
          % EV1 only admitted with reservation that nègre was what they primarily called Blacks in Mamou when he was young

      % Deborah Tauzin
        % (49:19)
        % Deborah (White Creole): Avant, c'était pas juste les Noirs. C'était les Français qu'a donné uh, les Espagnols ou comment, et là y avait des Noirs, mais après ça, les Blancs a commencé à fréquenter avec les Noirs, et ça fait y a deux races maintenant, mais avant, c'était tous les gens qu'étaient nés ici dans le Nouveau Monde, mais c'est plus comme ça, non.
      % Oliver Lesage
        % (67:20) [when asked what a Creole is, focuses on his hometown]
        % Oliver L. (Cajun): Là, ça dépend. Si tu es à Saint-Martinville, les Créoles sont les gens qui est de la première génération comme les Borne, les Renaud, qui sont venus de France. ... Là, il y a les Créoles qui sont des gens soit noirs ou mixtes qui parlent le français ou le couru-vini.
          % He went on to highlight that there's a sort of public debate playing out between using the first definition, the second definition, or both.

      Jack offered a particularly detailed and erudite description of Creoles, but it was not unusual for participants to recount some of what he said, especially the idea of being born in the colony.
      In Sentences \ref{sent:creole_lucille} and \ref{sent:creole_brian1}, Lucille Royer and Brian Roger, both Cajuns, related this sense of Creole, and in both cases they highlighted the children of French nationals being Creole rather than the children of anyone at all.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Lucille (Cajun): La Ville Platte, la paroisse Évangéline, a été vraiment fondée par beaucoup de soldats de Napoléon, ... donc c'est vraiment, c'est créole dans le sens de créole, pas dans le sens de couleur de la peau. C'était, you know, les enfants des colons. (39:10) \label{sent:creole_lucille}
        \item[] \longtrans{Lucille (Cajun): Ville Platte, Evangeline Parish, was really founded by a lot of Napoleon's soldiers, ... so it's really, it's Creole in the sense of Creole, not in the sense of skin color. That was, you know, the children of colonists.}
        \item Brian (Cajun): Quoi moi j'ai entendu de un Créole, c'est quelqu'un qui est né en-dedans l'État-Uni-, ina du monde qui a dit, quoi moi j'ai appris, si tu viens de la France, et puis tu maries quelqu'un, une autre Française, ta femme qui vient de la France, ça, eux-autres vient de la Louisiane. Eux-autres a un petit. Le petit-ça, c'est un Créole. (56:52) \label{sent:creole_brian1}
        \item[] \longtrans{Brian (Cajun): What I heard about a Creole, that's someone who was born in the United Sta-, there are people who said, what I learned, if you come from France, and then you marry someone, another French woman, your wife who's from France, that, they come from Louisiana. They have a little one. That little one, that's a Creole.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Lucille, in doing so, acknowledged that this understanding could be confusing by immediately bringing up the skin color definition, a confusion that could only come about in the context of Creoles being primarily understood as Black today.

      % Often specifically Europeans born in the colony
        % Arthur Rousseau
          % (49:21) [ancestry but not a color or ethnicity even just when he was a kid]
          % Arthur (Cajun): Quand j'étais jeune, le mot créole -- quand j'ai apprendre le mot -- le mot, c'était des offsprings of the people who came from the Old Country, settled here, and their offsprings were called Creoles. Didn't have anything to do with color or ethnicity.
            % Using "Old Country" leaves ambiguity, but suggests that a person had to be from a certain place rather than just born in Louisiana.
        % Austin Roy
          % (71:15) [Avoyelles families were from France directly]
          % Austin (Cajun): Wayne, well lui il est pas cadien parce que, well son père à lui, c'est ça vient de Pérou, but le bord à sa mère, c'est des Villanueva de la paroisse des Avoyelles. Ça c'est des Créoles blancs là-bas, ça fait lui, c'est un Créole blanc.
        % Lucille Royer
          % (39:10) [Napoleons soldiers made Ville Platte Creole]
          % Lucille (Cajun): La Ville Platte, la paroisse Évangéline, a été vraiment fondée par beaucoup de soldats de Napoléon, ... donc c'est vraiment, c'est créole dans le sens de créole, pas dans le sens de couleur de la peau. C'était, you know, les enfants des colons.
        % Brian Roger
          % (56:52)
          % Brian (Cajun): Quoi moi j'ai entendu de un Créole, c'est quelqu'un qui est né en-dedans l'État-Uni-, ina du monde qui a dit, quoi moi j'ai appris, si tu viens de la France, et puis tu maries quelqu'un, une autre Française, ta femme qui vient de la France, ça, eux-autres vient de la Louisiane. Eux-autres a un petit. Le petit-ça, c'est un Créole.

      % Some were roughly aware of when Creoles (in the original sense) began being racialized
        % Brian Roger
          % (57:51) [Civil War]
          % Brian (Cajun): Dans la guerre civile, avant la guerre civile, ça voulait pas, les Blancs voulaient pas être mêlés avec les Noirs, ça fait ils ont commencé dire si tu parles créole, ou bien si tu es créole, tu es noir, et puis si tu es blanc, tu es cadien ou bien américain.

      % New Orleans was mentioned a lot but was rarely the primary feature participants went with
        % Laura Laviolette
          % (57:26) [when asked what a Creole is]
          % Laura (Cajun): They came from, like, by New Orlean- Nouvelle-Orléans, but they, the islands, the, you know, like, you know. Ça c'est un Créole.
            % This reference to the Caribbean was brought up by several participants and feels like an expression of distance
        % Randal Chenevert
          % (59:11) [one of a number of different definitions he offered, leading into the European one]
          % Randal (Cajun): Y avait des histoires dans Nouvelle-Orléans: Creole aristocracy. C'était peut-être pas seulement noir, mais comme j'ai comprendre le vrai définition, la génération de Europeans qu'étaient nés ici dans le Nouveau Monde. C'est ça. Moi je comprends ça, et puis pour moi, les deux sont Creole.
          % (60:27) [he also went on to say this would make Acadians Creoles, as well]
          % Randal (Cajun): Dans le vieille Acadie, pour moi, strictly by definition, les enfants de ces premiers colons, c'est des Creole.

      The only participant to give the more accurate, broader original sense of Creole as anyone born in the colonies at all was Bruce Wiltz in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_bruce}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Bruce (Cajun): Moi, j'ai jamais entendu les gens qui s'identifiaient comme créoles avant peut-être dix ans passés, dix ans ou vingt ans peut-être. (37:18) \label{sent:creole_bruce}
        \item[] \longtrans{Bruce (Cajun): Me, I never heard people who identified as Creoles before maybe ten years ago, ten years or twenty years maybe.}
      \end{enumerate}
      He, however, went on to say that this would make him both Cajun and Creole, as well as making everyone in the US Creole, and so he rejected the idea.
      While his reasoning was not driven by any sort of ideological racism, it nevertheless upholds the racialized social system that places Cajuns as the default, White race and Creoles as the Others who cannot be Cajun.
      His statement also exemplifies that, for some participants, their ability to discuss earlier, non-racialized definitions of Creoles is unlikely to have come from an understanding they developed in their younger days.
      Indeed, two other Cajuns explained that they never heard the word \lexi{Creole} in their youth.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Judy (Cajun): Tu connais, j'ai réellement jamais connu ce mot, créole. Juste dernièrement, c'est comme si tout quelqu'un est créole. (63:18) \label{sent:creole_judy}
        \item[] \longtrans{Judy (Cajun): You know, I really never knew this word, Creole. Just recently, it's as if everyone is Creole.}
        \item Dennis (Cajun): Well, on usait pas ce mot \lexi{créole} dans ce temps-là. Non, c'était des uhm, on juste disait du monde noir ou des nègres, mais le propre nom, c'était des Créoles noirs. (38:06) \label{sent:creole_dennis}
        \item[] \longtrans{Dennis (Cajun): Well, we didn't use this word \lexi{Creole} at that time. No, that was uhm, we would just say Black people or negros, but the proper name, that's Black Creoles.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Dennis Oubre's explanation in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_dennis} is particularly striking as it transposed the common modern day understanding of Creole being Black to those people in his childhood who could have identified or been identified as Creole, suggesting a strong link between Blackness and Creoles for him.
      
      % Elizabeth Naquin
        % (18:53) [Creole wasn't a word used in Henderson when she was young]
        % Joshua (Interviewer): Quand vous étiez jeune, dans la communauté, inavait du monde qui disait, "Je parle créole," ou c'était tout quelqu'un disait, "Je parle français"?
        % EN: Mo étais pas connais le mot créole jusqu'à mo mo étais plus vieille. Mo étais pas entendre le mot créole. C'est juste no était parler français. Papa, li [i] parlait son cadien.
        % Joshua (Interviewer): Inavait pas ces distinctions entre cadien et créole et, pour le langage, pour les personnes?
        % EN: Non, mo rappelle le mari à ma sœur, mon beau-frère, li était élevé à Arnaudville, puis li était dit nous-autres, "No parle le bon français à Arnaudville," parce que li était parler cadien.
        
      % Although something of the opposite could be true, also, where Creole was what everyone said
        % Jerry Pierre Quintero
          % (32:18) [it was only Creole where he grew up]
          % JPQ: Où moi j'ai été né, c'est comme ça. On était appelés créole, parce que c'est une drôle de chose ça. On a appelé créole, surtout quand moi j'ai été élevé naturellement, les Noirs, tu connais? Y a trois ou quatre différents Créoles. Ina les Créoles, le monde vient des Espagnols, et inavait ça là, des Haïti, ... les Noirs et les Blancs dans ce temps-là, tu connais, mais c'est une drôle de chose. Ça s'appelait, uh nous-autres, les Blancs, s'appelaient créoles.
          % (38:24) [and more on that]
          % JPQ: Dans les Avoyelles, on parlait pour les Cadiens, mais on connaissait pas qu'un Cadien c'est.

      The link between Blackness and Creoles was in fact as common in definitions of Creoles as Acadian ancestry was in definitions of Cajuns.
      Sentences \ref{sent:creole_cynthia} and \ref{sent:creole_randal1} are just some of the statements expressing this idea.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Cynthia (Cajun): Moi, j'ai grandi, créole c'était noir. (38:02) \label{sent:creole_cynthia}
        \item[] \longtrans{Cynthia (Cajun): Me, I grew up, Creole was Black.}
        \item Randal (Cajun): Alentour ici, je connais pas si t'as perçu ça ou tu connais ça, asteur ça a venu, it evolved into un Creole c'est quelqu'un noir. (58:46) \label{sent:creole_randal1}
        \item[] \longtrans{Randal (Cajun): Around here, I don't know if you noticed this or you know this, now that became, it evolved into a Creole is someone Black.}
      \end{enumerate}
      For Rose Louvière, she included the option that a Creole could be a wealthy, educated person but specifically in New Orleans, far from where she grew up in Church Point.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Rose (Cajun): Les Créoles, pour moi, les Créoles étaient le monde de couleur ou bien instruit. ... Les mondes de créole de Nouvelle-Orléans est bien instruits. Wealthy, you know? (62:33) \label{sent:creole_rose}
        \item[] \longtrans{Rose (Cajun): Creoles, for me, Creoles are colored people or well educated. ... Creole people from New Orleans are well educated. Wealthy, you know?}
      \end{enumerate}
      New Orleans was not an uncommon theme when speaking about Creoles and is almost definitely a remnant of the Creole myth.
      Oliver Lesage in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_lesage} was not offering his definition of Creoles but rather attempting to determine the ethnicity of an alter whom he named but whom he did not know terribly well.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Oliver L. (Cajun): Uh, un homme noir, mais uh, uh créole, on dirait. Ouais, il est créole. (63:34) \label{sent:creole_lesage}
        \item[] \longtrans{Oliver L. (Cajun): Uh, a Black man, but uh, uh Creole, we would say. Yeah, he's Creole.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Olver expresses his thought process connecting Blackness with Creoles out loud, but that same thought process seemed to be at play when, for instance, Lillian Himel initially stated that she did not know any Creoles, paused, then considered a recently encountered acquaintence who was Black and named him as Creole.
      % Wendte
        % Wendte's participants often used ancestry as a qualifier for being Creole and often put this in terms of color, especially by qualifying Creoles as some sort of mix of peoples (pp.~179/181/183-184/188/218/279/298).
        % Creoles could thus be a mix of Black and White (p.~168) or some variation of a mix of European (\foreign{i.e.}, White), Black, and Indian (p.~200/218-219) or simply Black (pp.~182-183/191/201/219/277/284), whereas Cajuns were White (pp.~182-183/189/284-285/297-298).
        % There were exceptions, as well as in the data that will be presented here, where some Creoles insisted that they were neither Black nor White (pp.~275-276) or were not ``noir noir'' \gloss{black Black} (p.~278).
        % These more nuanced approaches seem to be efforts to navigate a label that has clearly come to mean Black so as to avoid the stigma -- which itself acknowledges that there is a stigma -- without completely disregarding their connections to Blacks through ancestry.
        % For Cajuns, however, the only exceptions made were among Texan Creoles (pp.~182/190), suggesting that their relative distance from Louisiana has somewhat weakened the White association.

      % Black
        % Arthur Rousseau
          % (49:42) [changed to be about color just since his youth]
          % Arthur (Cajun): But now it's all morphed to Creole mean Black: Black culture, Black cooking, Creole cooking.
        % Oliver Lesage
          % (63:34) [uses appearance to classify alter who he doesn't know well on a personal level]
          % Oliver L. (Cajun): Uh, un homme noir, mais uh, uh créole, on dirait. Ouais, il est créole.
        % Bruce Wiltz
          % (36:45) [acknowledges a historical version that highlights New Orleans and Europeans, but explains how Creole settled on Africans albeit mixed with Whites]
          % Brian (Cajun): Pour des années, quand moi j'ai grandi, d'après moi, moi je savais que le mot créole, au début, à la Nouvelle-Orléans, c'était un mélange de Français et les Espagnols, et puis là, c'est des années après ça, c'était les Africains, eh, qui s'appelaient des Créoles, eh, parce que je crois c'était un mélange de les Africains et les Blancs ou quelque chose comme ça. C'était des Créoles.

      The above participants who equated Creole with Black were all Cajuns.
      This does not mean that Creoles did not see Blackness in their understanding of Creoles, but they instead highlighted the idea that Creoles are racially mixed.
      Terry Guillot, who both ethnically and racially identified simply as Creole, was quite plain in stating that Creole is a mixed race in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_terry}, while Florence Gaspard even had a humorous anecdote that characterized Creoles as mixed in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_florence}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=senteces]
        \item Terry (Creole): C'est une race de monde mêlé. (41:49) \label{sent:creole_terry}
        \item[] \longtrans{Terry (Creole): It's a race of mixed people.}
        \item Florence (Creole): Comme mon maman était dit nous-autres, ``Li était un mixed paint.'' (91:03) \label{sent:creole_florence}
        \item[] \longtrans{Florence (Creole): Like my mama would tell us, ``He as a mixed paint.'}
      \end{enumerate}
      For James Cameron in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_james}, he provided examples of what sort of mixtures of people would lead to Creoles, and in every case, it was someone of African ancestry and of European ancestry.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item James (Creole): Un Créole, ça doit être une personne dans l'héritage mixte, mais ça doit avoir africaine, et français-African, espagnol-African, allemand-African, African, et ... beaucoup de Créoles à Nouvelle-Orléans étaient les gens libres. (40:10) \label{sent:creole_james}
        \item[] \longtrans{James (Creole): A Creole, that has to be a person with a mixed heritage, but that has to have African, and French-African, Spanish-African, German-African, African, and ... a lot of Creoles in New Orleans were free people.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Florence had also contextualized her anecdote in this way, although her examples included someone mixing with Spanish people, Indians, or Whites, that someone presumably being Black.
      In Sentence \ref{sent:creole_floyd}, Floyd Kerry only gave ``Colored'' people mixing with Whites as an example, but importantly he emphasized both that this was a painful thing for the former group and was really about enslaved women being violated rather than enslaved men.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Floyd (Creole): Dans les temps, les vieux, c'était quand les Blancs et puis la Couleur étaient vini ensemble et fait un petit, okay? C'était pas un bonne affaire pour les Couleurs. Dans ces temps-ça-là, yé étaient travailler dans le clos, et puis yé étaient prendre les femmes, les Couleurs, et puis, to connais, fait yé't'oler fait avec yé. (45:55) \label{sent:creole_floyd}
        \item[] \longtrans{Floyd (Creole): In the past, the old people, that was when Whites and the Colored were coming together and making a little one, okay? That wasn't a good thing for the Coloreds. At that time, they would work in the field, and then they would take the women, the Coloreds, and then, you know, do what they wanted to do with them.}
      \end{enumerate}
      This idea of pain and hardship in one's identity is not all that different from what Judy Soileau Courtade described for Acadians/Cajuns in Section \ref{sec:what_cajun}.

      % Racially mixed people
        % Samantha Primeaux
          % (31:58) [when asked if she identifies as Creole, after explaining that her ancestors were enslaved, she says]
          % SP: Il y a des Européens dans ma famille. Ils ont mélangé avec les personnes noires, alors ça veut dire que, je pense vraiment que je suis créole. Ça c'est pourquoi nous parlons français. C'était à cause d'esclavage.
        % Deborah Tauzin
          % (56:37) [talking about how Creoles need not be White]
          % Deborah (White Creole): Mais en Louisiane, il faut faire attention parce que y en a beaucoup qui a peu de sang de noir, eh?
        % Judy Soileau Courtade
          % (63:34) [Black man, White woman rather than the inverse]
          % Judy (Cajun): Je suis pas créole, parce que je connaissais personne de couleur, et c'est ça moi je crois c'était. Moi, je croyais c'était quelqu'un qu'avait venu ici, et peut-être un homme noir avait marié une femme blanche, et là ils étaient des Créoles, les bébés.
        % Gene Delcambre
          % (49:05) [most clearly of all draws the connection between gender and race in this system]
          % Gene (Creole): The two people that was always free: a White man and a Black woman. Them two that was always free, because they could always be together. They didn't have no Black man with a White woman. They kill you.

      Those who equated Creole with Black were all Cajuns, whereas those who equated Creole with mixed were all Creoles.
      On the one hand, this may be a case of having more nuance to one's one self-identification than to the identification of others, but there is also the possibility that this is a result of a racial ordering of things.
      In the broader US, being Black assigns one a very low social status.
      While the Creoles in Louisiana in this study appeared to see themselves as part of that broader group, the addition of a racially mixed background can be a way to dull the stigma that comes along with being Black.
      In effect, they can, and did, show solidarity with Blacks nationwide, but the door is also open to argue that they are not quite the same either.
      It is a sort of compromise, not entirely different from passing as White for those who can, as will be discussed in Section \ref{sec:life_experiences}.
      On the other hand, for Cajuns, there is no need to add this nuance to Creoles.
      The lot of this latter group is of no particular concern for the default race in the hierarchy, so a simple equation of Creole with Black is perfectly suitable.
      None of the participants here showed any sort of ideological racism leading them to do this, but they are influenced by the racialized social system within which they exist.

      Terry Guillot, above, described Creole as a race, but this view was not shared by all Creole participants.
      Florence Gaspard and Tracy Roth, for example, both rejected that view.
      Owen Webre, in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_owen} was even more forthright with this rejection when I asked him about it, saying that I had met a Creole with that view.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Owen (Creole): Mo crois, je crois quand même, les gens de Natchitoches, on a parlé avec un groupe des gens qui dit qu'ils sont les descendants des Français, qui disent qu'ils sont créoles, et on a demandé, ``Mais, qu'est-ce que ça veut dire, ça?'' Parce que c'est vraiment, ce n'est pas une race. C'est plutôt une culture. (51:42) \label{sent:creole_owen}
        \item[] \longtrans{Owen (Creole): I believe, I believe even, the people of Natchitoches, we spoke with a group of people who say that they're descendants of the French, who say that they're Creole, and we asked, ``Well, what does that mean?'' Because it's really, it's not a race. Rather, it's a culture.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Owen saw Creole as a culture rather than a race, and as with Cajuns, Creole cultural traits and practices were the first things several participants discussed when asked what a Creole is.
      Florence's explanation of Creole qualities in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_florence} is similar to the qualities previously given for Cajuns, particularly being hardworking and the importance of getting along with others which she went on to explain at lenght.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Florence (Creole): C'est quelqu'un qui travaillé dur, et la vie qui était dure, mais li était bon. No apprendre un tas, et no peux apprécier ça no gain. (67:19) \label{sent:creole_florence}
        \item[] \longtrans{Florence (Creole): That's someone who worked hard, and life was hard, but he was good. We learned a lot, and we can appreciate what we have.}
      \end{enumerate}
      While these then are very likely accurate descriptions for a large number of Creoles, they are not necessarily what distinguishes Creoles.
      % Wendte
        % Characterizing one's own group in positive terms
          % Another aspect of discourse that relates to using group traits as a proxy of racialization is the attempt of racialized people to downplay the importance of racial markers by focusing on positive traits when describing themselves.
          % In one case, a Texan Creole defined being Creole as being ``where your heart lies'' (p.~136), whereas a Louisianian Creole explained that being a Creole means that one is able to adapt and live off of anything (p.~205).
          % This approach to counteracting negative characterizations of Creoles occurred in the present study, as well.

      % People with cultural practices
        % Florence Gaspard
          % (94:37) [after desegregation of schools]
          % Florence (Creole): Si to étais pas l'aimer les Blancs, well to étais dans tracas, parce que yé saient battre.
        % Owen Webre
          % (43:15) [when asked, was somewhat reluctant to give a direct answer about what a Creole is, instead talked about the difficulties enslaved Africans had to work through]
          % Owen (Creole): Mo gain penser de ça, parce que c'est pas vraiment un individu. C'est plutôt le concept.
            % Part of what he highlighted was that "il faut accepter tout le monde" (46:21).
        % Terry Guillot
          % (22:22) [religion of Creoles, not a necessary condition but a state of affairs]
          % Terry (Creole): Tout notre monde, tous les Créoles, autour d'ici, ils estiont tous catholiques.

      One specific cultural practice that was referenced by several participants as being Creole was the playing of Zydeco music.
      As Lucille Royer explained in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_lucille}, the local accordion music of South Louisiana was at one time simply called French music but is now called Cajun music.
      In truth, this is only half of the picture, as another genre grew out of the same tradition and is today called Zydeco.
      Just as Cajun music is associated with Cajuns, Zydeco is associated with Creoles, as is evident in Sentences \ref{sent:creole_brian2} and \ref{sent:creole_randal2}, both produced by Cajuns.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Brian (Cajun): Quand tu penses de zaricot, c'est musique noire, mais le monde blanc asteur l'aime, moi, moi j'aime zaricot. (61:48) \label{sent:creole_brian2}
        \item[] \longtrans{Brian (Cajun): When you think about Zydeco, that's Black music, but White people now like, me, I like Zydeco.}
        \item Randal (Cajun): Les musiques zaricot, ça c'est les Creoles qui jouent ça. (59:03) \label{sent:creole_randal2}
        \item[] \longtrans{Randal (Cajun): Zydeco music, it's Creoles who play that.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Another Cajun, Errol Stoufle, gave an interesting account of a Zydeco musician, Troy, sometimes playing Cajun music, as well, in Sentence \ref{sent:creole_errol1}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Errol (Cajun): Troy va jouer un tas de la musique cadienne, mais li joue ça d'une différente manière, tu connais? Avec une différente accordéon, avec une différente clé, tu connais? (5:05) \label{sent:creole_errol1}
        \item[] \longtrans{Errol (Cajun): Troy will play a lot of Cajun music, but he plays that in a different way, you know? With a different accordion, with a different key, you know?}
      \end{enumerate}
      When Troy plays Cajun music, Errol explained that he does so with a different instrumentation.
      Indeed, a common different between the two genres is that Zydeco is typically played on a full piano keyboard accordion and Cajun music on a much smaller single row diatonic accordion \parencite[pp.~28-29]{kuhlken_geography_1991}.
      Troy does, however, regularly play the latter type of accordion, and as this instrument limits the musical key that can be played, it seems unlikely that Troy plays Cajun songs in different keys from what are normally expected.
      What is perhaps more likely is that the distinction between Cajuns and Creoles is so strong that Errol perceives Cajun music as being somehow inherently different if a Creole is playing it even if he does not consciously recognize that the only difference is the musician's identity.
      % Wendte
        % Both Texan and Louisianian Creoles used closely related musical genres as representations of Creoles and Cajuns as one way to accomplish to set the boundaries of the two groups (pp.~139/207-208/211).
        % For example, one participant seemed to suggest that Creoles and Cajuns or Whites were segregated or segregated themselves in terms of the sort of music shows each would go to, zydeco shows for the former and Cajun music shows for the latter (pp.~207-208).
        % In these discussions, the association of broad US racialized categories were used relatively interchangeably with Creole and Cajun so that one might also refer to Blacks playing and listening to zydeco and Whites to Cajun music.
        % What makes these examples stand out further is that, despite the many similarities between these two forms of accordion music, one of the participants, himself a zydeco musician, suggested that the difference between the genres is that bass notes are not played in Cajun music (p.~140) when in fact they are.

      % Zydeco is Creole
        % Deborah Tauzin
          % (50:22)
          % Deborah (White Creole): The Creole, autour de Opelousas et des places comme ça, le zarico, la musique zarico, ouais.
        % Errol Stoufle
          % (4:13)
          % Errol (Cajun): Mais là, comme samedi, tu viens, no gain la musique créole avec Troy Sandoz. Ça c'est samedi qui vient¨. No fait cinq fois par mois la musique zarico.
          % (32:56) [defined Cajuns culturally and does the same for Creoles, but their culture is different]
          % Errol (Cajun): Un Créole, c'est manière comme un Cadien, tu connais, mais yé yé parlent différence, tu connais? C'est le culture est un petit peu différente, la manière yé cuit, la manière yé yé fait leurs vies, tu connais?
          
      Both Randal Chenevert and Errol Stoufle also singled out another cultural practice that they associated with Creoles, and that was the use of tomatoes in cooking, as exemplified in Sentences \ref{sent:creole_randal3} and \ref{sent:creole_errol2}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Randal (Cajun): Quand tu vas à Nouvelle-Orléans, les gombos sont pas ça. C'est rouge. Ça met du tomate dans, et des okras, et des gombos, ça fait un tas du monde d'ici dit ça c'est pas gombo là-bas, mais c'est gombo. C'est juste le Creole. (61:58) \label{sent:creole_randal3}
        \item[] \longtrans{Randal (Cajun): When you go to New Orleans, the gumbos there are not that. They're red. They put tomato in, and okra, and okra, so a lot of people from here say that that's not gumbo over there, but it's gumbo. It's just Creole.}
        \item Errol (Cajun): Mo mo l'aime le manger créole. ...
        \item[] Joshua (Interviewer): Vous avez un plat préféré qui est créole?
        \item[] Errol: To peux faire gombo. To peux fais étouffé, mais uh
        \item[] Joshua: Ça c'est créole?
        \item[] Errol: Un gombo, ouais. Yé cuit ça différent, tu connais? Cadiens fait gombo itou, mais les Créoles fait un différent gombo.
        \item[] Joshua: Quoi c'est la différence?
        \item[] Errol: Well, ça yé met dans le gombo. Mais, peut-être un Cadien va cuit un gombo avec du roux puis la viande. Un Créole va peut-être fait un gombo avec des tomates dans le roux. ...
        \item[] Joshua: C'est bon comme ça?
        \item[] Errol: Mo pas connais. Mo mo je l'aime pas ça. \label{sent:creole_errol2}
        \item[] \longtrans{Errol (Cajun): I like Creole food. ...}
        \item[] \longtrans{Joshua (Interviewer): Do you have a favorite dish that's Creole?}
        \item[] \longtrans{Errol: You can make gumbo. You can make étouffé, but uh}
        \item[] \longtrans{Joshua: That's Creole?}
        \item[] \longtrans{Errol: A gumbo, yeah. They cook that differently, you know? Cajuns make gumbo, too, but Creoles make a different gumbo.}
        \item[] \longtrans{Joshua: What's the difference?}
        \item[] \longtrans{Errol: Well, what they put in the gumbo. Well, maybe a Cajun will cook a gumbo with some roux and meat. A Creole will maybe make a gumbo with tomatoes in the roux. ...}
        \item[] \longtrans{Joshua: Is it good like that?}
        \item[] \longtrans{Errol: I don't know. I don't like that.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Errol's discussion is particularly interesting.
      He begins by saying that he likes Creole food.
      When asked to be more specific about a dish that he likes, he names gumbo, a dish that Cajuns make as well, but explains that Creoles put tomatoes in their gumbo.
      However, when asked if gumbo with tomatoes in it tastes good, he immediately responded that he does not know because he does not like gumbo like that.
      What had begun as Errol expressing an openness to Creoleness became the exact opposite when the discussion became less abstract, so much so that Errol's final utterance in this exchange includes one of only \Sexpr{tablesParticipant$firstSg$`Errol Stoufle`["je"]} tokens of \lexi{je} for 1sg rather than his usual Creole-marked \lexi{mo}, as if to signal greater distance from the dish.
      This quick shift in stances resembles at least in part the phenomenon of White individuals attempting to name Black individuals whom they know, when in fact they do not really know any, to signal that they are not closed off to racial Others, a phenomenon that also occurred when Cajuns named alters for this study.
      % Wendte
        % Such exaggerations of the difference between Creole and Cajun musics, and by extension Creoles and Cajuns, also showed up when \citeauthor{wendte_tale_2020}'s (\citeyear{wendte_tale_2020}) participants spoke about cooking.
        % Texan and Louisianian Creoles suggested that Cajuns either make gumbo differently (p.~215) or simply use less seasoning (p.~143).
        % Not only did the former explanation acknowledge that Creoles and Cajuns make the same dish, but the latter explanation was given as a vague matter of degree of seasoning.
        % The implication is that Creoles and Cajuns do not have signficantly different culinary practices if any despite their attempts to distinguish these things as being indicative of distance between Creoles and Cajuns.

      % Town that one is from
        % Deborah Tauzin
          % (6:36)
          % Joshua (Interviewer): La ville [her hometown] s'appelle Créole?
          % Deborah (White Creole): Oui, oui Créole.
          % Joshua (Interviewer): Tout le monde là était créole ou?
          % Deborah (White Creole): Non, personne était créole. Ça ne savait pas qu'y avait une langue créole, tu vois?
            % Notably, she ties Creole identity to a way of speaking which she later criticized, all this despite identifying as Creole herself.

      Regardless of what aspect of Creole identity participants were speaking of, the racialization of Creoles was evident of in their discourse.
      Cultural practices that are shared with Cajuns are somehow different.
      They have varied ancestry that included Europeans, but that of Creoles was discussed in terms of blood and racial mixing with other lower status groups, whereas Cajuns were only recognized as having intermarried with other Europeans.
      Most prominently, however, Creoles were consistently described as Black, whereas Cajuns, who are more necessarily White, were almost never described as White.
      This sets the social position of Creoles to be equivalent to that of Black Americans in general and below the Cajun default, which is permitted to be more racially invisible.

    \subsection{Comparison of life experiences}
      \label{sec:life_experiences}
      While the more general questions of what Cajuns and Creoles are for my participants shed light on racialization in South Louisiana, the above analysis has only hinted at their life experiences.
      In a racialized social system, though, one would expect the lower status group to go through experiences that the higher status group does not.
      In this case, Creoles should expect to have faced hardships that Cajuns have not.
      This is not to say that Cajuns do not have their own difficulties in life, but rather that those difficulties are not unique to them in the way that Creoles' would be.
      
      % Terry Guillot
        % (71:19) [when the topic of people speaking differently from town to town]
        % Terry (Creole): Tu vois, quoi qui arrive là là, ça vient d'être une race tout le tour. Monde parle pareil. Ça mange pareil. Un tas des affaires, ça va faire pareil.

      One of those shared life experiences is poverty.
      This was recounted by Cajuns like Laura Laviolette, who explained that she only first saw a twenty dollar bill when her husband started working in a shipyard in Sentence \ref{sent:life_laura}, and Judy Soileau Courtade, whose mother was worried that the fabrics they used made them look poor despite everyone actually being poor in Sentence \ref{sent:life_judy}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Laura (Cajun): Le premier il a été, j'ai vu un twenty dollar bill pour le première fois. On était pauvres. (21:31) \label{sent:life_laura}
        \item[] \longtrans{Laura (Cajun): The first time he went, I saw a twenty dollar bill for the first time. We were poor.}
        \item Judy (Cajun): Ma mère, pour elle, c'est comme si c'était quelque chose qui disait t'étais pauvre, et elle voulait pas je fais rien avec ça, mais je connais mieux, tu connais? C'était on était tous la même. Tout quelqu'un était pauvre à ce temps-ça. Oh juste on connaissait pas on était pauvres. (24:50) \label{sent:life_judy}
        \item[] \longtrans{Judy (Cajun): My mother, for her, it is as if that was something that said that you were poor, and she didn't want me to do anything with that, but I know better, you know? It was that we were all the same. Everyone was poor at that time. Oh just we didn't know that we were poor.}
      \end{enumerate}
      This sentiment of not wanting to say that one was poor was shared by Tracy Roth, a Black Creole, in Sentence \ref{sent:life_tracy1}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Tracy (Creole): No dit nou était pauvres, but to étais pas dis  étais pauvre. (29:46) \label{sent:life_tracy1}
        \item[] \longtrans{Tracy (Creole): We say that we were poor, but you didn't say that you were poor.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Another Black Creole, Florence Gaspard, shared an anecdote in Sentence \ref{sent:life_florence1} that is worth printing here with minimal abbreviations.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Florence (Creole): Quand mon mari mouru, femme là vini chez moi, et li't'apè crier parce que li dit mon mari, c était si tellement un bon monde. Li dit li 'mandé mon mari, ``Combien mo doit à toi pour fait mon la cour?'' Li dit mon mari dit li, ``Donne-no ça t'oler,'' et li dit, ``Na pas personne qui dit to, `Donne-moi t'oler.' Yé dit to comment yé'ler.'' ... C'était parce que no était devient de les récoltes, et no était connaît comment c'était dur, so un petit brin l'argent, c'était couru loin. (37:26) \label{sent:life_florence1}
        \item[] \longtrans{Florence (Creole): When my husband died, that woman came to my place, and she was crying because she said that my husband, that was such a good person. She said that she asked my husband, ``How much do I owe you for doing my yard?'' She said that my husband told her, ``Give us what you want,'' and she said, ``There's no one who tells you, `Give me what you want.' They tell you how much they want.'' ... That was because we came from farming, and we knew how hard it was, so a little bit of money, that went far.}
      \end{enumerate}
      It shows that her husband, a man who took cleaning jobs for a living, was in a position in their community to help out a woman who was even less fortunate than himself.
      
      % Poverty was a common theme for both
        % Cynthia Robichaux Savoie
          % (81:19) [talking about a man who was doing a baking program in the poorest school in the area]
          % Cynthia (Cajun): In the poorest section of Saint Landry Parish is where they [the kids] came from, et pour la plupart, des Noirs.
        % Owen Webre
          % (7:30) [talking about when he was growing up]
          % Owen (Creole): Et aussi, no était pas gain un bathroom dans la maison. To étais gain pour couru dehors.
        % Terry Guillot
          % (14:56) [while talking about how they didn't wear shoes when they were young, and it was okay until the streets got paved]
          % Terry (Creole): On avait pour apprendre pour marcher sur les gravois nu-pieds.
          % (15:26) [no electricity when young]
          % Terry (Creole): Quand moi j'étais un petit garçon, on avait pas d'électricité.
        % Tracy Roth
          % (14:23) [speaking about things being hard when he was younger]
          % Tracy (Creole): But c'est pas comme ça asteur. Oh ouais, oh ouais, c'était dur. C'était dur quand no't'ap been nés élevés.
          % (41:16) [explaining how he didn't know about saving money in banks]
          % Tracy (Creole): C'est que quand mo mo commencé travailler tous les jours, mo étais pas connais rien pour la banque. C'est que quand to sais couru à la banque, to donnes yé ton chèque. Yé saient charger ça pour cash ton chèque, because to étais pas gain une carte. So now, inavait une femme -- elle l'aimé moi -- elle sait dit moi comme ça, "To peux serrer l'argent là."
        % Gene Delcambre
          % (69:56) [also didn't know about savings accounts]
          % Gene (Creole): He said, "We'll open you a savings account." I said, "A saving account?" I said, "What's that? I don't know what a savings account is. I don't come from nowhere. I ain't thinking about saving. I don't make but eighteen dollars."
        % Floyd Kerry
          % (28:39) [his grandparents in the 1950s and 1960s]
          % Floyd (Creole): Mon gros-mère et père, yé étaient profit sharing. C'est ça yé't'ap fait. Ça fait, quand to profit sharing, tout quoi to élevais dans le clos, to gain pour donnes soixante percent pour homme qui gain property.
            % As he continues to say, the youngest kids in the family, then, would be able to go to school, but only because the older kids were helping out on the farm.

      In some way, the work that Creoles and Cajuns did was also similar, as in the case that Arthur Rousseau, a Cajun, related in Sentence \label{sent:life_arthur}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Arthur (Cajun): Je rappelle monsieur Bee. Monsieur Bee était un ami de mon père. Monsieur Bee, il était noir, et il était un poseur de briques comme mon père, un maçon. Lui et mon père étaient des amis, mais comment tu dis, they knew the difference now. Then, it still wasn't, you know, like it's better today than it was then. (50:14) \label{sent:life_arthur}
        \item[] \longtrans{Arthur (Cajun): I remember Mr Bee. Mr Bee was a friend of my father. Mr Bee, he was Black, and he was a bricklayer like my father, a mason. He and my father were friends, but how do you say, they knew the difference now. Then, it still wasn't, you know, like it's better today than it was then.}
      \end{enumerate}
      I had been asking Arthur about Creoles, and in response, what Arthur was expressing about his father and his father's Black friend was that, even though they performed the same work, they were not given the same social status due to the friend being Black.
      The experience was thus filtered through a racialized social system that made the lives of the two men quite different.

      In other cases, Creoles were described as working for Cajuns, instead.
      It is quite possible that the Cajuns shared in the work that they hired Creoles to do, but the fact that it was the Cajuns who owned the products of that labor makes their work inherently different.
      In the examples of this in Sentences \ref{sent:life_dennis1} and \ref{sent:life_deborah}, I was asking Dennis Oubre, a Cajun, and Deborah Tauzin, a White Creole, if there were Creoles in their hometowns, respectively.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Dennis (Cajun): Pas de trop. Chaque grande ferme engageait un ou deux, mais ça restait sur la ferme, et mon grand-père avait un, et moi et lui, ... c'était le seul je connaissais. (32:53) \label{sent:life_dennis1}
        \item[] \longtrans{Dennis (Cajun): Not too many. Each big farm hire one or two, but they stayed on the farm, and my grandfather had one, and he and I, ... that was the only one that I knew.}
        \item Deborah (White Creole): Mon grand-père avait les escalves à la maison. J'ai grandi avec les Noirs. On avait beaucoup, ouais.
        \item[] Joshua (Interviewer): Oh, ouais? Y a beaucoup de Noirs à Créole?
        \item[] Deborah: Non, ils travaillaient pour mon grand-père, mais oui, mais c'était la même famille de tous les Noirs. C'était les esclaves, et oh, mon grand-père a amené un bateau de femmes pour marier avec les gens. Non non, y a pas beaucoup de Noirs à Cameron, non. (58:55) \label{sent:life_deborah}
        \item[] \longtrans{Deborah (White Creole): My grandfather had slaves at the house. I grew up with Blacks. We had a lot, yeah.}
        \item[] \longtrans{Joshua (Interviewer): Oh, yeah? There are a lot of Blacks in Creole?}
        \item[] \longtrans{Deborah: No, they worked for my grandfather, but yes, well that was the same family for all the Blacks. They were slaves, and oh, my grandfather brought a boat of women to marry the people. No no, there aren't a lot of Blacks in Cameron, no.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Dennis explained that Creoles would only come to work on the farms there, included his grandfather's.
      Although Dennis gave no indication of harboring any racial ideology -- in fact, he went on to say that knowing this man gave him a ``meilleur cœur'' \gloss{better heart} for Creoles -- his instinct was to describe his grandfather as ``having one'' as if Creoles were possessions for these farms.
      This may have simply been a poorly worded phrase, but Deborah's statements were much less ambiguous.
      She was a wordly woman, but was still able to relate that her grandfather had enslaved people and brought women, presumably enslaved women, to her hometown to marry the men who were enslaved there, whose descendants were still close enough to the family that she went on to explain that one of them took care of her as a child.
      The this woman was known by a derogatory, racist nickname, as well, suggesting that the history of ideological racism in her own family was still present at least until when she was young.

      % Alice Lemaire
        % (43:22) [referring to her in-home nursing job that a Black woman also did]
        % AL: Y avait moi le jour and a little Black lady at night.
      % Alice Lemaire
        % (10:58) [Blacks coming to help with the boucherie]
        % AL: On était habitués avec des Noirs parce que, quand Pop faisait boucherie avec ses cochons, on avait des voisins, y avait une négresse qui venait aider à Mom.
      % Judy Soileau Courtade
        % (51:59) [making the point that Cajuns and Creoles were friendly with each other]
        % Judy (Cajun): In fact, la femme que t'as vue à Maurice, ... elle disait, tu connais elle les appelait des Nègres. C'est ça. On a tous dit ça quand on était petits, et elle dit il était comme quelqu'un dans la famille. Il travaillait pour eux, et elle dit, quand son enfant était né, son mari était son godfather, ... et quand son mari est mort, elle dit il a venu voir son mari, et à ce temps-ça, le monde blanc voulait pas que le monde noir vient à la maison. Leur corps était dans la maison, mais elle dit il a venu. Il a passé dans la chambre, la porte en arrière, et il a venu, et il a parti, et elle dit, la semaine après, quand il a venu, il a venu dans la maison dans la porte en avant.
      
      Cajuns also discussed facing stigma and discrimination, however.
      In Sentence \ref{sent:life_bruce}, Bruce Wiltz recounted a discussion he witnessed where a mother from Marksville wanted to be called French rather than Cajun because the latter was stigmatized.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Bruce (Cajun): Mais, une fois, il habitait ici, il a dit ça à sa mère, un jour il dit, ``Mais Mom, on est tous des Cadiens.'' ``Oh non,'' elle dit, ``on est pas des Cadiens. Nous-autres, on était français.'' Eh? Parce que les Cadiens, c'était, it was a lower class, une basse classe, eh? (40:17) \label{sent:life_bruce}
        \item[] \longtrans{Bruce (Cajun): But, one time, he lived here, he said that to his mother, one day he says, ``But Mom, we're all Cajuns.'' ``Oh no,'' she says, ``we aren't Cajuns. Us, we're French.'' Eh?}
      \end{enumerate}
      This was perhaps a rare phenomenon, though.
      He went on to explain that this was the only time he had heard a family express the desire to be called French rather than Cajun.
      A more commonly shared example of discrimination that Cajuns shared was linguistic in that F\&C speakers were said to be punished for speaking the language in school.
      Oliver Gomez gave an example in Sentence \ref{sent:life_gomez}, but as with every other time the participants for this study mentioned this punishment, it was never firsthand experience but rather the experience of earlier generations of Cajuns, suggesting that their status has changed over the last 100 years or so.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Oliver G. (Cajun): Puis moi, j'étais jamais puni pour parler français, mais mes parents a été punis pour parler français. (15:59) \label{sent:life_gomez}
        \item[] \longtrans{Oliver G. (Cajun): Then me, I was never punished for speaking French, but my parents were punished for speaking French.}
      \end{enumerate}
      This makes the school punishment theme not all that different from the admiration Judy Soileau Courtade was expressing back in Sentence \ref{sent:cajun_judy1} for the hardships the Acadians had faced despite not offering any sign that she herself had faced discrimination.

      % Brian Roger
        % (49:05) [not a personal experience, but Cajun stigma was a thing in the 20s and 30s]
        % Brian (Cajun): Je crois, pour plusieurs années, inavait un tas du monde qui était embarrassé être nommé des Cadien.
      % Errol Stoufle
        % (11:12) [implies that it wasn't him directly him who was punished]
        % Errol (Cajun): Yé étaient pas l'aimer ça, quand to étais causer français dans l'école, so yé yé poussé plus langage de l'anglais, tu connais? Yé étaient look down toi, tu connais, pour parler français. ...
        % Joshua (Interviewer): Est-ce que vous vous étiez puni pour ça ou?
        % Errol (Cajun): Well, des fois, yé étaient puni les petits à l'école pour ça.
      % Brian Roger
        % (50:05) [more clearly talking about his father rather than himself]
        % Brian (Cajun): Quand lui, il a fini l'école, il avait trois ans de français dans Arnaudville. ... Mais, tout quelqu'un tu parles qui est plus vieux, ça disait ça les fouettait.
      % Judy Soileau Courtade
        % (2:12) [parents punished]
        % Judy (Cajun): Ça parlait, mon père et ma mère parlaient juste en français, ça se fait quand ils ont été à l'école, ils étaient punis, parce que ça pouvait pas parler en anglais.
        
      % Cajuns as disciminators
        % Dennis Oubre
          % (27:37) [disappointment at what he felt was a change in Cajuns becoming less accepting of others]
          % Dennis (Cajun): J'ai vu un mauvais changement les derniers vingt ans. J'ai des amis de Canada et de la France qui dit cinquante ans, les Cadiens étaient différents que les Cadiens on trouve aujourd'hui. Rednecks, Trumpers, c'est des Cadiens qu'a perdu leur vision d'être acceptance de tout le monde. Ça, on était pas comme ça en avant, au commencement. On a accepté les Indiens. On a accepté les Espagnols. Tous les autres, on dit tout acceptance. On l'aime tout le monde d'être ensemble et d'être soutenu. ... Ça c'est, j'ai été élevé comme ça.
            % This sentiment was rare among Cajuns, however

      For Creoles, discrimination was very much personal.
      Cajuns themselves were aware of this.
      Dennis Oubre talked about the existence of segregation when he was younger as in Sentences \ref{sent:life_dennis2} and \ref{sent:life_dennis3}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Dennis (Cajun): C'était interdit pour aller à l'église ou à l'école. (33:35) \label{sent:life_dennis2}
        \item[] \longtrans{Dennis (Cajun): It was prohibited to go to the church or to the school.}
        \item Dennis (Cajun): Landon pourrait pas rentrer dans la maison. (35:24) \label{sent:life_dennis3}
        \item[] \longtrans{Dennis (Cajun): Landon [a Creole] couldn't enter the house.}
      \end{enumerate}
      He also spoke proudly of his hometown being one of the first towns in Louisiana to begin desegregating.
      Segregation was what Cajuns primarily discussed when speaking about the discrimination faced by Creoles, however.
      As can often be expected in racialized social systems, it is often only the clearest cases of explicit institutional racism that stand out to those who are not the victims of racialization.

      % Alice Lemaire
        % (10:26) [separate Black and White schools, irrational fear of Blacks]
        % AL: Et juste avant mon école, y avait une école de Noirs. Tu connais, c'était pas mêlé dans ce temps-là. Ça se fait, moi et mes deux petits frères, on passait loin dans le fossé parce qu'on avait peur des petits nègres. Pourquoi on avait peur? Moi, je connais pas.
          % Despite the terms Alice used, she showed no signs of ideological racism. In fact, she wanted to name her first girl after a Black girl who road her husband's bus because she loved the girl so much (14:05).
        % (11:49) [this was still the case later when she was married]
        % AL: Mon mari drivait un school bus, juste des Noirs.
        % (12:19) [but it did change while her husband was still doing that work, but the change wasn't all good]
        % AL: Quand il ont été mêlés, les Blancs et les Noirs dans son bus, ça se battaient. ... Ça aimait pas les Noirs, tu connais.
        % (27:02) [talking about church segregation when she was young]
        % AL: À la messe, les Blancs s'assisaient d'une partie de l'église, et les Noirs s'assisaient sur une- on était pas mêlés à notre messe.
        % Joshua (Interviewer): Oh, non? Mais c'était la même église?
        % AL: Ouais, la même église, même prêtre.
        % Joshua (Interviewer): Le prêtre était blanc ou noir?
        % AL: Oh, blanc.
        % Joshua (Interviewer): Et c'était comme ça pour tous les prêtres ou...?
        % AL: Y avait des prêtres noirs en quelques places je pense, but il était blanc.
        % Lucille Royer
          % (43:58) [speaking about seeing a group of Blacks in costume performing a call and response and walking from one side of her town to another]
          % Lucille (Cajun): C'était des Noirs, et j'avais peur. Je regardais par la fenêtre, les gros yeux, et j'étais une petite fille, et mes parents ont pas expliqué. Je pense ça disait, "Oh, ça c'est les nègres qui passent."
            % This wasn't segregation, but it was that same sort of irrational fear that racialized social systems engender. She was otherwise in awe of the scene.

        Black Creoles spoke about the discrimination that they faced in much more detail.
        Owen Webre, in Sentence \ref{sent:life_owen}, was treated as a token \parencite{kanter_effects_1977} in his professional capacities, being moved from one job location to another to fulfill a diversity quota.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Owen (Creole): J'ai été sélectionné pour un poste à [a high school] comme assistant principal, ça fait j'ai pris ça, mais j'ai commencé là, mais j'ai pas resté là trop longtemps. Non, on a décidé que je dois travailler à [a different high school]. Je crois que c'était à cause de ma race. À ce temps-là, il faut avoir quand même un Noir. (22:53) \label{sent:life_owen}
          \item[] \longtrans{Owen (Creole): I was selected for a post at [a high school] as assistant principal, so I took that, but I started there, but I didn't stay there too long. No, someone decided that I have to work at [a different high school]. I believe that that was because of my race. At that time, it was necessary to have at least one Black.}
        \end{enumerate}
        Gene Declambre offered quite a few examples of discrimination in his life, two of which are reproduced in Sentences \ref{sent:life_gene1} and \ref{sent:life_gene2}.
        \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
          \item Gene (Creole): C'est comme ça là. C'était les Blancs  étaient dit toi quoi faire. Les Blancs  étaient dit les mondes Couleur quoi faire. (2:59) \label{sent:life_gene1}
          \item[] \longtrans{Gene (Creole): It was like that then. It was that the Whites would tell you what to do. Whites told colored people what to do.}
          \item Gene (Creole): No jouait contre un et l'autre. J'ai jamais joué contre les Blancs, because les Blancs  étaient pas voulaient mettre pas avec les nègres. (35:54) \label{sent:life_gene2}
          \item[] \longtrans{Gene (Creole): We would play against one another. I never played against Whites, because Whites didn't want to be put with negroes.}
        \end{enumerate}
        The first was very early in the interview in response to a question about why he moved as a child, to which he responded very plainly that they simply had to do what Whites told them to do, and in that case it was for his family to stop farming and move.
        The second sentence was later in his life when he was a baseball player who could not play again White baseball players.
        Gene's language and Owen's are both particularly interesting in contrast to these statements.
        Owen in fact preferred Creole-marked subject pronouns but spoke in a very standardized way when relating this story, as he did for any academic or professional topics.
        Gene, on the other hand, used a mix of Creole-marked and Cajun-marked pronouns in his second sentence, which he in fact did throughou the interview where he generally preferred Cajun-marked pronouns other than for 3pl.
        He had, however, demonstrated that he could use Creole-marked pronouns, and through the shifts in his syntax, it would not be surprising if he normally did use these pronouns but chose not to with me.
        In this respect, the language of both speakers suggest that they felt they had to hide their Creoleness to some degree when not speaking to another Creole.

        % Florence Gaspard gave a less specific but highly revealing account of discrimination in Sentence \ref{sent:life_florence2}.
        % She described a hierarchical system with three levels where Whites were at the tops, Cajuns in the middle, and Creoles at the bottom.
        % In this system, it was the job of Cajuns to keep Creoles down in order to get ahead themselves, whereas Whites seemed to exploit the situation in whichever way would serve their needs.
        % She went on to explain that, even though Whites would sometimes help Creoles, they would not do things like sell them land as they would do for Cajuns.
        % Florence, then, saw Cajuns in something of a middle social status akin to the Pardos in Brazil, the Coloureds in South Africa, and even Creoles in at times throughout the Americas, as discussed in Section \ref{sec:united_states}.
        % This, of course, is not something Florence related as personally experience discrimination, but it did not appear to be ancient history, either.

        % \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        %   \item Florence (Creole): Yé la vie c'était pas comme no-tiens. Yé étaient gain un petit brin plus que nous-autres des fois, parce que yé étaient aider un et l'autre un tas, et là navait les Blancs. C'est pas les mêmes que les Cadiens, okay? Un Blanc, yé étaient gain un tas. Un Cadien  était pas gain un tas comme un Blanc, so les Cadiens étaient travailler un tas pour des Blancs, parce que yé étaient vini de Canada. Yé étaient pas vini en haut dans ça. Yé yé étaient vini l'autre bord, so quand yé vini, c'est yé étaient pauvres. Yé étaient proche aussi pauvres qu'un Créole. Proche. Mais, yé étaient gain un petit brin plus, parce que yé saient aider les Blancs ... Mais, un Cadien, ... yé saient pas aider un Créole much, pas un tas, mais un Blanc sait aider un Créole plus. (82:44) \label{sent:life_florence2}
        %   \item[] \longtrans{Florence (Creole): Their life wasn't like ours. They had a little bit more than us sometimes, because they helped one another a lot, and then there were the Whites. That's not the same as the Cajuns, okay? A White, they had a lot. A Cajun didn't have a lot like a White, so Cajuns worked a lot for Whites, because they came from Canada. They didn't come from up high in that. They came from the other side, so when they came, they were poor. They were almost as poor as a Creole. Almost. But, they had a little bit more, because they would help the Whites ... But, a Cajun, ... they wouldn't help a Creole much, not a lot, but a White would help a Creole more.}
        % \end{enumerate}

        % Florence Gaspard
          % (86:06) [the poverty that Cajuns faced is what pitted them against Creoles]
          % Florence (Creole): Les Cadiens, yé yé l'aiment pas trop les Créoles. Les Blancs s'adonnent plus vite. Les Cadiens qu'ap'ssayer gain quelque chose. Yé't'ap'ssayer gain la terre. Yé étaient pas gain la terre.
            % She explained that Cajuns could buy land from Whites, but it was only later that Creoles could buy land from Whites, and even then it would take working for Whites for decades for just a small amount of land.
        % Tracy Roth
          % (81:37) [when asked what a Cajun is]
          % Tracy (Creole): Un Cadien, pour moi, c'est un monde ... li pas'ssayer adonner avec les autres.
          % (93:27) [passing]
          % Tracy (Creole): Ina un tas de monde mo mo connais qu'ap'ssayer passer pour blanc.
        % Gene Delcambre
          % (2:59) [speaking on moving because they had to stop farming]
          % Gene (Creole): C'est comme ça là. C'était les Blancs étaient dit toi quoi faire. Les Blancs étaient dit les mondes Couleur quoi faire.
          % (7:56) [his boss at the garage liked him and would put him in charge while he was away]
          % Gene (Creole): Blanc là, il aimait pas ça. C'est, "Come on Princess. Go do that." "No, he told you to do that."
            % He quit the job for fear of this eventually causing more problems.
          % (33:39) [couldn't play football]
          % Gene (Creole): Okay, j'ai joué la pelote. Oh ouais, joué la pelote.
          % Joshua (Interviewer): Quel game de pelote? Le football?
          % Gene (Creole): Oh, baseball. Oh, inavait pas football pour les nègres là là.
            % For both Gene (36:22) and Tracy (97:43), both baseball players, Jackie Robinson stood out in their minds enough that they brought him up independently.
          % (40:30) [when he was younger, Black policemen couldn't do anything to Whites and was better off not wearing his uniform if he went into Lafayette]
          % Gene (Creole): Un nègre était un policeman, mais il peut refuser rien à un Blanc. Tu peux voir Blanc là apè battre là là, mais tu fais rien. ... T'es gone à Lafayette, change-toi. Mets-toi quelque chose d'autre.

      Acceptance of Creoles was also related in the discourse of Creoles themselves, showing that a racialized social system does not exclude instances of acceptance and mutual aid, but these acts do not constitute the overwhelming pattern, and each example below also acts as evidence of racialization.
      Even Gene Delcambre was able to talk about an instance where White men helped him, albeit he did so in English.
      His situation involved receiving a ticket while driving.
      He went to court with his White boss and a White lawyer whom his mother luckily knew.
      The judge attempted to fine him 250 dollars initially, a significant amount given  that he made 18 dollars per week at that time, but his boss vouched for him and his lawyer argued for him, resulting in a fine of 20 dollars instead.
      While it was laudable that two White men were willing to help him, the fact that they needed to in the first place is suggestive of a racialized social system.

      Florence Gaspard provided a story that involved taking her grandson to prayer events where they were the only ``Couleurs'' \gloss{Coloreds} there.
      In Sentence \ref{sent:life_florence3}, she explained that her grandson was initially apprehensive, but she explained the importance of getting along with all types of people, and this resulted in him receiving help with school from one of the White women there.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Florence (Creole): To gain pour adonner avec tous les couleurs. C'est comme ça to la vie va d'être bon. Si to juste adonnes juste avec une, c'est pas assez. \label{sent:life_florence3}
        \item[] [he agreed and attended the event repeatedly after that]
        \item[] Florence (Creole): Et là li dit, ``Mais to connais maman, femme là, oh ça c'est une nice femme. C'est la plus nice femme mo jamais connais,'' et so elle aidé li quand li couru à l'école, to comprends? (69:46)
        \item[] \longtrans{Florence (Creole): You have to get along with every color. That's how your life will be good. If you just get along just with one, that's not enough.}
        \item[] \longtrans{[he agreed and attended the event repeatedly after that]}
        \item[] \longtrans{Florence (Creole): And then he said, ``Well you know mama, that woman, oh that's a nice woman. That's the nicest woman I've ever met,'' and so she helped him when he went to school, you understand?}
      \end{enumerate}
      The fact that her grandson was aware enough of race to begin with shows that this was a positive occurrence set in the context of a racialized social system.
      Tracy Roth presented another anecdote in Sentence \ref{sent:life_tracy2} that would only be possible in the context of a racialized social system despite representing positive intergroup actions.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Tracy (Creole): Mo joué un tas de la pelote, et no couru un tas les places, et mo étais seul Noir, et tous les Blancs, les autres Blancs, yé étaient coutume 'mander, ``Comment vous-autres peut gain nègre là pour jouer avec ça?'' Et yé saient tout le temps dit, ``L'a jouer avec nous-autres because li bon,'' et then, ``Oh, mo peux pas fais ça. Mo peux pas,'' et yé saient dit comme ça, ``C'est pas sa couleur qu'ap jouer la pelote. C'est li.'' C'est quoifaire mo l'aime li si tant. (95:31) \label{sent:life_tracy2}
        \item[] \longtrans{Tracy (Creole): I played a lot of baseball, and we went to a lot of places, and I would be the only Black, and all the Whites, the other Whites, they had a habit of asking, ``How can you all have that negro you play with?'' And they would always say, ``He'll play with us because he's good,'' and then, ``Oh, I can't do that. I can't,'' and they would say like this, ``It's not his color that's playing ball. It's him.'' That's why I love him so much.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Unlike Gene Delcambre, Tracy was able to play baseball against White players, but this was only possible because his White teammates supported him.
      He needed the aid of those at the top of the racial hierarchy to subvert that hierarchy that clearly existed.

      At every level of life experience, the discourse of Creoles and Cajuns suggests that Creoles have been racialized.
      Cajuns are not immune to hardship, but much of it that is salient for them has not been experienced firsthand other than poverty.
      That poverty was also not experienced in the same way for Cajuns as it was for Creoles as the latter could not shake their low status even when doing the same work as Cajuns.
      Creoles, on the other hand, showed themselves to be quite personally familiar with discrimination.
      This does not mean that they did not have positive life experiences with non-Creoles, but those positive experiences generally represented non-Creoles helping them subvert a racialized social system that is ever-present.

    \subsection{Creole speech versus Cajun speech}
      When speaking about language, both Creoles and Cajuns were able to speak of differences between each other.
      At times, these differences are downplayed, as in the statement in Sentence \ref{sent:different_speech_floyd} where Floyd Kerry, a Black Creole, focuses on local varieties being relatively similar unlike how they are both much different from how the French in Europe speak.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Floyd (Creole): C'est pas un gros différence. To vois, ici dans la Louisiane, les Créoles et puis les Cadiens restent ensemble, ça fait les Cadiens et puis les Créoles, yé parlent pas la français comme les Français parlent le france. (52:36) \label{sent:different_speech_floyd}
        \item[] \longtrans{Floyd (Creole): It's not a big difference. You see, here in Louisiana, Creoles and Cajuns live together, so Cajuns and Creoles, they don't speak French like the French speak French.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Given the racialization of his identity, however, he has an incentive to promote closeness between the two groups rather than distance.
      This theme of acceptance of others came up more with Creoles than with others.
        
      % Arthur Rousseau
        % (52:43) [some Cajuns mix French and Creole]
        % Joshua (Interviewer): J'ai rencontré un homme, un Cadien. À mon oreille, il parlait créole en fait, mais il me disait, "Je parle français."
        % Arthur (Cajun): Ouais, c'est un mélange de français et créole.
        % (53:21) [Creole is a dialect of French]
        % Arthur (Cajun): C'est un dialecte.
      
      More often, though, participants were regularly able to distinguish.
      Oliver Lesage, a Cajun, offered two examples of Creole-marked speech in Sentences \ref{sent:different_speech_lesage1} and \ref{sent:different_speech_lesage2}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Oliver L. (Cajun): Si t'olé parler en nègre, en créole, couru-vini, mo mo capable faire ça, aussi. (1:07) \label{sent:different_speech_lesage1} \\
        \item[] \longtrans{Oliver L. (Cajun): If you want to speak in negro, in Creole, Couru-Vini, I'm capable of doing that, too.}
        \item Oliver L. (Cajun): \emph{Elle} s'appelle Mildred, alors quand elle elle arrive, là no gain pour parler comme ça. \emph{Li} dit, ``Oliver, comment to yé, nègre?'' Et, ``M'apè fais okay aujourd'hui.'' (2:21) \label{sent:different_speech_lesage2}
        \item[] \longtrans{Oliver L. (Cajun): Her name is Mildred, so when she arrives, then we have to talk like this. She says, ``Oliver, how are you, negro?'' And, ``I'm doing okay today.''}
      \end{enumerate}
      In the latter example, the switch involves him going from using \lexi{elle} to using \lexi{li} to refer to Mildred, showing the salience of subject pronouns in the distinction between the varieties.
      Also notable is that both of his demonstrations include the word \lexi{nègre}, whose translation in Louisiana is quite difficult.
      It has long been used in a rather term of endearment among Cajuns, even appearing in the refrain of the popular Cajun music song \song{Lâche pas la patate} released by Jimmy C Newman in 1973.
      It has also been used as a pejorative term.
      In this case, the intent was clearly endearment, but that it was thought be appropriate for articulating Creole speech either exemplifies a latent association, reinforces an association, or both.
      The term will be seen in a number of other examples, some that are more ambiguous and some that are less so.
      % L1 only understood nègre to be N-word, but the topic came up because a Louisianian used it with him as a term of endearment (191)

      % Gene Delcambre
        % (42:15) [Creoles from different places speak differently]
        % Gene (Creole): Yé parlent différent. Là, comme à Lafayette, Carencro, Scott. ... Toi, tu vas dis 'let's go' uh, "Mais j'ai viens à la grocerie." ... Mo couru la grocerie.
        % Lucille Royer
          % (46:19) [supports Gene's statement]
          % Lucille (Cajun): Les Noirs à la Ville Platte parlaient français cadien d'après ce que moi je me rappelle.

      The term in fact came up within the same discourse theme but in a much more clearly derogatory form.
      In Sentence \ref{sent:different_speech_bruce1}, Bruce Wiltz recalls hearing the speech of Creoles described as such.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Bruce (Cajun): J'ai entendu dire c'était le français nègre. (68:09) \label{sent:different_speech_bruce1}
        \item[] \longtrans{Bruce (Cajun): I've heard it said that it was Negro French.}
      \end{enumerate}
      A Cajun who did not grow up around people who called themselves Creoles, giving this information as reported speech distances him from any possible role in such disciminatory practices but also highlights the understanding that Creole speech is stigmatized.
      Owen Weber, a Black Creole, confirms that this stigma existed in Sentence \ref{sent:different_speech_owen}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Owen (Creole): Nous-autres, \emph{no} était parler créole dans la maison ou à la maison et dans les voisinages. Si \emph{on} voyageait de le village comme ça, de le le territoire ou, \emph{on} disait que, ``Laisse pas les mondes connaît que to't'apè parler ça, parce que yé va dit que to pas éduqué ou quelque chose. Ina quelque chose pas bien avec toi.'' (15:55) \label{sent:different_speech_owen}
        \item[] \longtrans{Owen (Creole): Us, we would speak Creole in the house and in the neighborhood. If we were traveling around the town like that, around the region or, we would say, ``Don't let people know that you were speaking that, because they will say that you're not educated or something. There was something not right with you.''}
      \end{enumerate}
      When asked if people in Breaux Bridge used to say that they were Creole, he explained that this was not something they wanted to say publicly for fear of being looked down on.
      Owen style shifted considerably during our interview, which is not being robustly analyzed here.
      However, his shifts appeared to coincide with whether he was speaking about non-Creoles or academic matters, in which cases he would use Cajun-marked pronouns.
      In this example, that meant using \lexi{no} for 1pl at first while speaking from his own viewpoint to using \lexi{on} when implying the presence of non-Creoles.
      This suggests the existence of a certain amount of segregation between Creoles and Cajuns that makes it meaningful to style shift along those lines, confirming the social distance that the network analysis here suggested.

      Despite that distance, Cajuns were generally cognizant that it is not only Creoles who have Creole-marked speech patterns.
      When making this observation, it was very common to highlight specific towns where this phenomenon exists.
      In Sentences \ref{sent:different_speech_austin} and \ref{sent:different_speech_bruce2}, Henderson and Catahoula were highlighted while also giving examples of what the variety sounds like, each of which includes Creole-marked subject pronouns.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Austin (Cajun): Elle vient de Henderson, et puis to ca' dis li parle un petit brin créole là. (81:02) \label{sent:different_speech_austin}
        \item[] \longtrans{Austin (Cajun): She's from Henderson, and so you can say that she speaks a bit of Creole there.}
        \item Bruce (Cajun): Et eux, ils ont venu de autour de Catahoula, et ça parlait un peu de le créole aussi, eh? ``Mo gain li, to gain li,'' et c'est la seule fois moi j'avais entendu ça. (46:21) \label{sent:different_speech_bruce2}
        \item[] \longtrans{Bruce (Cajun): And them, they came from around Catahoula, and they spoke a bit of Creole also, eh? I have it, you have it, and that's the only time that I had heard that.}
      \end{enumerate}
      The phenomenon was most clearly put into racial terms in Sentence \ref{sent:different_speech_cynthia}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Cynthia (Cajun): Les Créoles, mais ouais, ça parle différent que nous. ``Mo mo étais couru.'' \gloss{I went.} ``Mo étais couru. No était gain.'' ... Il y a des Noirs qui parlent le français comme nous-autres, mais il y a des Blancs qui parlent le créole comme les Noirs, et Cecilia qui est sept miles d'ici, pour la plupart, les Blancs, ils parlent créole, et on disait ils se parlent nègre. Ça disait pas ils se parlent créole. (45:13) \label{sent:different_speech_cynthia}
        \item[] \longtrans{Cynthia (Cajun): Creoles, well yeah, they speak differently than us. ``I would go.'' \gloss{I went.} ``I would go. We had.'' ... There are some Blacks who speak French like us, but there are some Whites who speak Creole like Blacks, and Cecilia which is seven miles from here, for the most part, Whites, they speak Creole, and we would say to each other that they speak negro. They wouldn't say that they speak Creole to each other.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Cynthia Robichaux Savoie was asked if Cajuns and Creoles speak differently, to which she responded that they did, gave some examples that included Creole-marked subject pronouns, and then explained further using the terms White and Black rather than Cajun and Creole, implicitly making the association between the local social categories and broader racialized social categories.
      She also once again brought up the word \lexi{nègre} for characterizing Creole-marked speech in Cecilia, a town that was also brought up by Brian Roger, Mary Bonvillain and Arthur Rousseau to talk about Whites using Creole-marked speech, as well as Bruce Wiltz, Lillian Himel and Oliver Lesage to talk about Creole-marked speech being present in general.
      In this case, this was said to be what White speakers with such speech patterns would call their own language, although this does not mean that the term was being used for endearment.
      Indeed, I had encountered White speaker during my research who did not want to speak F\&C because his speech is what he would call N-word French, a term that he was unwilling to say out loud but rather hinted at until he was sure that we both understood to what he was referring.

      % Brian Roger
        % (59:34) [brings up Cecilia after being asked if people today think Creoles are Black and Cajuns are White]
        % Brian (Cajun): Ina un tas du monde qui dit ça, parce que, tu vois, par exemple en Cecilia, la langue là-bas c'est plus créole, "mo gain, to gain," les mots comme ça, "couru, mo couru, to couru," et puis Arnaudville, c'est cadien ou bien français. ... Ça fait, le français à Arnaudville, ina un tas du monde va dire c'est un, j'aime pas user le mot, mais c'est un meilleur français.
          % We returned to this later in the interivew (64:45), where he further explained that he knows Blacks ("Noirs") who speak "cadien" or "français" but older Whites ("blanc") in Cecilia speak Creole.
      % Mary Bonvillain
        % (40:48) [Cecilia and Arnaudville]
        % MB: Beaucoup de monde croit que le français cadien, c'est pour les Blancs, et que le français créole, c'est parlé par les Noirs, mais il y a des gens blancs, comme autour de Cecilia et Arnaudville, qui parlent le français créole.
        % (42:54) [she does go on later to say that in Carencro, where she once taught, the belief matches what she experienced]
        % MB: Les gens de Carencro, les Blancs parlaient français cadien. Les Noirs parlaient français créole.
      % Arthur Rousseau
        % (52:22) [Cecilia and Breaux Bridge]
        % Arthur (Cajun): Y a beaucoup des Blancs qui parlent créole dans Cecilia et Breaux Bridge.
      % Bruce Wiltz
        % (67:46) [Cecilia, Coteau Holmes, Catahoula]
        % Joshua (Interviewer): Je suppose que c'était pas aussi fréquent [speaking Creole] à Lafayette que d'autres villages autour de Lafayette peut-être ou?
        % Bruce (Cajun): Non, je crois pas. Je crois c'était comme autour de Cecilia, Coteau Holmes, Catahoula.
      % Lillian Himel
        % (45:40) [explaining that there were no Creoles where she grew up, then switches to talking about language]
        % Lillian (Cajun): Tu vois, j'étais élevée dans l'ouest, dans la paroisse, et le monde qui parle créole, dans mon idée, ç'habite un tas au ras Pont Breaux et Cecilia.
          % So these towns weren't always invoked to highlight Cajuns who speak Creole but were also invoked simply to highlight where one hears Creole (and in this case would meet Creole people)
      % Oliver Lesage
        % (2:07) [saying something similar to Lillian]
        % Oliver L. (Cajun): Et c'est comme ici. À Cecilia, beaucoup de gens parlent couru-vini.
        % (66:27) [general observation about Creole speakers]
        % Oliver L. (Cajun): Mais, y a beaucoup de gens ici qui parlent couru-vini mais qui ne sont pas noirs.

      When not highlighting specific towns, the general concensus was indeed that Creoles use Creole-marked features.
      Even when non-Creoles were discussed as using Creole-marked features, this was done as an addendum to what was considered the obvious connection of Creoles using Creole-marked features.
      Cajuns also, at times, placed some distance between their speech and that of Creoles by suggesting a completely different origins for the two varieties.
      In the case of Creole, the Caribbean is brought into the frame in Sentences \ref{sent:different_speech_arthur} and \ref{sent:different_speech_brian}.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Arthur (Cajun): A lot of the Blacks that settled these regions [Lafayette] were from the islands [Caribbean], somewhere from the islands, and the islands were French. (50:46) \label{sent:different_speech_arthur}
        \item Brian (Cajun): Le monde qui viensait de les îles en-dedans le Caribbean a ramené le français, le créole, la langue créole, en-dedans pour qu'on peut travailler dans les clos de canne, sugarcane, ça fait moi je trouve, d'après moi, le, enfin, ils ont une table créole en Arnaudville. C'est proche tous les Noirs. (60:44) \label{sent:different_speech_brian}
        \item[] \longtrans{Brian (Cajun): The people that came from the islands in the Caribbean brought back French, Creole, the Creole language, so they can work in the cane field, sugarcane, so I find, in my opinion, the, anyway, there's a Creole table in Arnaudville. It's almost all Blacks.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Both participants hedged these statements by explaining that they may be wrong, acknowledging their ignorance on Creole matters which likely stems from having little contact with Creoles, which is a natural result when a group has been racialized.

      Creoles were likewise aware that Cajuns generally speak differently than Creoles.
      Unlike Cajuns, some Creoles spoke about this in terms of the effort they put forth to understand Cajuns' way of speaking.
      This asymmetry, where the burden of making things work falls on the racialized group, is indicative of racialization.
      In Sentence \ref{sent:different_speech_tracy}, Tracy Roth explained that it was incumbent on Creoles to learn how Cajuns speak if they wanted to get ahead.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Tracy (Creole): To peux trapper la manière yé parlent, comme la manière yé parlent, ça yé a dit, to vois? Un Cadien, to gain pour apprendre comment li parle, then si to peux trapper ça, then to connais où to restes. (89:09) \label{sent:different_speech_tracy}
        \item[] \longtrans{Tracy (Creole): You can pick up the way they speak, like the way they speak, what they will say, you see? A Cajun, you have to learn how he speaks, then if you can pick that up, then you know where you stand.}
      \end{enumerate}
      Rachel Chenevert was not as committed to this idea in Sentence \ref{sent:different_speech_rachel}, but she did draw the connection once again between the broad category of White and the local category of Cajuns.
      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Rachel (Creole): Les mondes, yé vient. Y'apè causer. ... It's a lot of White people come and say, you know, they speaking Cajun a lot of time, but some I don't really understand too good, Cajun sometime, but I let them know. I said, ``I don't speak Cajun. I'm a Creole.'' ... But sometime, ... na des fois n'a causer jusqu'à n'a comprendre un à l'autre, you know? (22:16) \label{sent:different_speech_rachel}
        \item[] \longtrans{Rachel (Creole): People, they come. They're talking. ... It's a lot of White people come and say, you know, they speak Cajun a lot of time, but some I don't really understand too good, Cajun sometime, but I let them know. I said, ``I don't speak Cajun. I'm Creole.'' ... But sometime, ... there are times we will talk until we will understand one another, you know?}
      \end{enumerate}

      % Sometimes those who use Creole-marked features do not talk about it as Creole
        % Florence Gaspard
          % (43:16) [how parents told them stories because they didn't have books]
          % Florence (Creole): Yé étaient fait le story pour toi yé étaient dit toi ça en français.
        % Floyd Kerry
          % (12:57) [family who spoke French have passed away]
          % Floyd (Creole): Ina un tas des mondes asteur là, yé parlent pas français dans mon famille, to connais?
          % (69:14)
          % Floyd (Creole): Le français et le créole, c'est la même affaire. C'est juste un petit peu cassé.
        % Errol Stoufle
          % (9:27) [talking about how "French" was useful for his job]
          % Errol (Cajun): Tu connais, yé étaient des vieux Cadiens, tu connais? Yé étaient connaît le monde. Yé étaient parler français. ... Une raison mo a eu le job parce que mo étais connais un tas du vieux monde d'ici, puis mo étais parler français.
      
      The way in which Creoles and Cajuns spoke about F\&C was consistent with what one would expect to find in a racialized social system.
      Distinctions between the racialized group, in this case Creoles, and others are salient enough that their appearance in language variation is apparent to residents.
      Broader racialized social categories are often associated with the local categories, and those associations are typically to the detriment of Creoles.
      As would also be expected in a racialized social system, Cajuns were content to express or create distance with Creoles, whereas Creoles felt a need to reduce that distance as their lack of access to social resources means that social distance to those who have more access works against Creoles but not necessarily against Cajuns.

    %%% Probably not useful %%%
    % Regional differences
      % Arthur Rousseau
        % (37:44) French in Lafourche isn't "formel" like Lafayette
        % Arthur (Cajun): À la paroisse Lafourche, c'est pas formel comme c'est ici. C'est formel parce qu'il y a l'université qu'est uh tu parles le langue français. Alfred Boulee, il a fait beaucoup des films. Et pas juste Alfred, Thibodeaux, Lawrence, il a fait beaucoup des chansons dans Canada. Quand Thibodeaux va à Canada, ça roule le tapis rouge pour lui.

  \section{Discussion}

